<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, Japan to Reopen Fishery Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea and Japan have agreed
to hold talks in Tokyo on Wednesday for a revision of a bilateral
fishery agreement, a Foreign Ministry official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was made last Saturday at a meeting between
Ryu Kwang-sok, director-general for Asian and Pacific affairs of
the ministry, and his Japanese counterpart Koreshige Anami.
</P>
<P>
The two also hoped to conclude the fishery talks as soon as
possible, said the official.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and Japan failed to narrow difference over the
revision of the 1965 bilateral fisheries accord at the
mid-September meeting in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The bottleneck of the negotiations is the issues related to the
Tokto islets (Takeshima islets in Japanese), on which Japan
proposed joint management of the seas around the islets but South
Korea said it was unacceptable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
