<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Militants Sentenced in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian State Supreme
Security Court today sentenced three Islamic militants to ten
years in prison, and the fourth to a 3-year prison term, the
Egyptian Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The four were accused of association with the out-lawed Islamic
Group in Aswan, about 900 kilometers south of Cairo, according to
the agency.
</P>
<P>
They were also convicted of murder and illegal possession of
firearms.
</P>
<P>
The court said the four convicts had "systematically adopted
the terrorist tactics of murder, bloodshed and sectarian sedition
as a means to disrupt security and stability in the country with
the purpose of overthrowing the existing ruling regime."
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Group, the largest militant fundamentalist group in
Egypt, is fighting a violent war against the government to install
a rigid Islamic rule. A total of 1,244 people have been killed
since the campaign began in March 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
