<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Holds Military Exercises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Georgian Defense Minister Vardiko
Nadibaidze today said the large-scale military exercises now being
performed by the Georgian army do not threaten Abkhazia's
security, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a press conference in Tbilisi, capital
of Georgia, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
All of Georgia's 40,000 armed forces were raised to full alert
at the initial stage of the exercises, while more than 10,000
servicemen moved to the Senaki district in Western Georgia, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The exercises authorized by President Eduard Shevardnadz
started at the beginning of the week and involve all of Georgia's
arms-bearing government organs, he added.
</P>
<P>
U.N. observers and Russian peacekeepers in Abkhazia had
protested against the military exercises which are held in the
direct vicinity of the neutral zone with Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed disagreement with the protest saying
that the only training ground where Georgia can hold exercises of
this scope is located near Senaki and the exercises do not border
on the neutral zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
