<HEADLINE> Ill-Health Causes Low Productivity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Prevalence of ill-health among
workers and growing insecurity of employment have been identified
as factors undermining productivity in the southern African
region.
</P>
<P>
In a report on productivity in the southern African region
issued here today, noted economist of Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions Godfrey Kanyenze said ill health among working people had
reached unacceptable high levels.
</P>
<P>
"The unacceptable levels of ill health among working people
due to poor working and living conditions should be recognized as
undermining productivity," said Kanyenze.
</P>
<P>
He said human resource was critical to any country's
development and should be prioritized.
</P>
<P>
Some people have blamed the raging HIV/AIDS scourge on the
high rate of absenteeism in most work places.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 10 percent of Zimbabwe's population is said to be
carriers of the aids-causing HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, given the growing recognition that insecurity of
employment undermines productivity, enhancement of employment
security should be recognized as a contributor to productivity
gains," said the economist.
</P>
<P>
He said the education system in southern Africa should be
responsive to the needs of individual economies.
</P>
<P>
"Adult literacy should be part and parcel of a human resource
development strategy,'' said Kanyenze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
