<HEADLINE> UK to Tighten Controls After Nuclear Sub Parts Lost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The British Ministry of Defense
(MoD) has pledged to tighten up its procedures after some
components ordered for the country's Trident nuclear submarine
have gone missing.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of key parts for Britain's 12 billion pound (about 19
billion US dollar) Trident nuclear submarine have vanished on its
way to Britain, according to a report in today's Sunday Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the lost parts, which did not contain any
nuclear material, left the manufacturers in the United States and
went missing when the consignments reached the Trident base in
Faslane, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report, a spokesman of the MoD said that it
does not know where the components have gone, but it does not
think fraud or terrorism are involved.
</P>
<P>
"The Trident system deals with around 70,000 receipts a year.
These losses represent less than 0.1 percent of the total," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "Since our investigation, we have tightened up our
procedures when ordering our vast amount of equipment." 
</P>
</TEXT>
