<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Resumes in South Africa's Kwazulu-Natal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed in
four separate attacks overnight when violence resumed in the
Richmond area of the Kwazulu-Natal province, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Richmond area had seen frequent clashes between supporters
of the African National Congress (ANC) and the Zulu-based Inkatha
Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
The new wave of violence came at a time when peace seemed to
be returning to the area after months of turmoil, said South
African National Defense Force spokesman in the area Frans
Schreuder.
</P>
<P>
He said a report of the first attack was received at about 9
p.m. (1900 GMT) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
When security forces arrived on the scene they found one dead
body and rounds of spent cartridges. Five men were arrested and
questioned about the attack.
</P>
<P>
"While we were still busy questioning them, more reports came
in of shots being fired. We went to investigate and found five
more bodies in different areas in the Richmond area," he said.
</P>
<P>
Cartridges from AK47s and R4 rifles and 9-mm-caliber pistols
were found on the various scenes of shootings.
</P>
<P>
Schreuder was unable to say whether the incidents were linked,
SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
"It's too early to say. They could all be linked to one group
of attackers or there could be several. We will have to
investigate further," Schreuder was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
It has not yet been officially confirmed but Shreuder's
initial reports indicate that victims of the incidents were all
local ANC supporters, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
The Richmond area saw large-scale violence earlier this year
until the arrest of former ANC strongman Sifiso Nkanbinde on 18
charges of murder. The arrest without bail of the powerful leader
and other suspects in the Richmond area led to a period of
relative peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Concerned Over US Aircraft Carrier's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran today expressed its grave
concern over the deployment of USS Nimitz aircraft carrier in the
Persian Gulf, terming the U.S. naval fleet as a threat to regional
security, according to the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Navy Commander Admiral Abbas Mohtaj was quoted as saying the
presence of foreign powers, mainly the United States, in the
region is illegitimate and threatens the security of the region.
</P>
<P>
"The arrival of tens of U.S. warships in the sensitive region
of the Persian Gulf is regarded as a major cause of tension and
insecurity at this part of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The presence of alien forces is aimed at heightening tension
and selling millions of U.S. dollars worth of arms to the Arab
countries in the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi noted that the growing friendly atmosphere between Iran
and the regional states has made the redeployment of the
U.S. warships in the Persian Gulf seen as an act in desperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the dispatch of the USS Nimitz aircraft carrier to the
Persian Gulf is an attempt to misportray the Persian Gulf as
trouble spot.
</P>
<P>
"The Americans are dissatisfied with the growing confidence and
friendship between Iran and its neighboring Muslim states in the
region and see the current atmosphere as harmful to their
illegitimate interests in the Persian Gulf," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said that Iran believes in strengthening relations
and friendship with its neighboring states and that the peace and
stability in the sensitive region of the Persian Gulf is directly
linked with the interests of all states in the region.
</P>
<P>
The United States said Friday that it dispatched the aircraft
carrier battle group to the Persian Gulf in the wake of Iranian
incursions into a U.S. -enforced "no-fly zone" in Southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iranian warplanes bombed camps of Iranian opposition group
Mujahedeen Khalq (people's holy warriors) organization in southern
Iraq on September 29.
</P>
<P>
U.S. forces deployed in the region currently include five
Tomahawk-capable destroyers, three frigates and two
minesweepers. The U.S. Fifth Fleet is based in the Gulf country of
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The battle group on route to the Persian Gulf comprises the
aircraft carrier USS Nimitz, with about 80 tactical aircrafts on
board, along with two cruisers, one destroyer, one frigate, an
attack submarine and support ship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
