<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-05 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli MPs Request Parliamentary Debate on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Thirty Israeli Knesset
(parliament) members have requested a parliamentary debate on the
attack of Hamas leader in Amman last week, Israel Radio reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The 30 Knesset members, most of them from the opposition, have
signed today the request for convening a Knesset special session
next Monday to discuss the alleged Israeli involvement in the
attack of Hamas leader Khaled Masham in Amman, the Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Mashal was attacked on September 25 in Amman by two "tourists"
holding forged Canadian passports. So far there is no confirmation
on who should be responsible for this attack, but there are strong
implications that the Israeli security service "Mossad" was behind
the attack.
</P>
<P>
After today's cabinet meeting, the Israeli government said in
a statement that right now it refrains from commenting on
this attack.
</P>
<P>
This means that the Israeli government has at last admitted
its responsibility for the attack, Israeli state TV Channel 1 said
this evening.
</P>
<P>
Shimon Peres, former Prime Minister and Knesset member from
the opposition Labor Party, today criticized the Benjamin
Netanyahu government's involvement in the attack, saying such
action could only harm Israel's friendly ties with Jordan and
cause political unstability in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties today also asked Netanyahu to resign to
shoulder the entire responsibility for the attack.
</P>
<P>
Declaring the use of its passports by foreign agents to
be unacceptable, Canada has already recalled its ambassador to
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry today expressed its regret again over
Canada's decision, hoping the friendly relations between the two
countries should not be damaged by this incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
