<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baltic Mayors Conference Ends in St. Petersburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The first conference of Baltic
mayors wound up today in St. Petersburg with a statement signed by
the participants, the Itar-Tass news agency reported from Russia's
second-largest city St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
The final statement declared their readiness for broad
cooperation and supported the idea of spreading regional
cooperation onto the Arctic zone, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The conference aimed to promote integration of the Baltic
region in Europe of the 21st century through development of
long-standing historical relations between cities.
</P>
<P>
Conference participants outlined a strategy of cooperation in
environmental protection, transport, culture, education and
personal security.
</P>
<P>
They decided to support the Russian initiative on creation of
Baltic Humanitarian University and approved an initiative of the
Petersburg administration to create a unified transport corridor
"Baltic bridge" as a plan that corresponds to the European
transport policy and helps economic development of the Baltic
region.
</P>
<P>
The conference was attended by heads of 16 cities of Russia,
Germany, Poland, the Baltic and Scandinavian countries, as well as
representatives of six international organizations from European
centers -- Paris, Bordeaux, Warsaw and Berlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
