<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Church Leader Urges to Cancel Africa's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Desmond Tutu, President of
the All Africa Conference of Churches (AACC), today urged
international financial institutions to cancel Africa's debt.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Tutu in his keynote address to the
seventh general assembly of the AACC which is underway at the
United Nations conference center here.
</P>
<P>
Tutu said, "we ask our friends who stood by us in the dark
days of oppression and injustice to join the new moral crusade to
have the debt canceled following the biblical principle of
jubilee."
</P>
<P>
By the "jubilee", he was referring to a campaign underway to
have the creditor nations and institutions cancel Africa's debt
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics available, the external debt of
African countries increased from 328.7 billion U.S. Dollars in
1995 to 340.5 billion U.S. Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The debt service payment of african countries was 24 billion
U.S. Dollars in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
