<HEADLINE> Palestinian: Success of Negotiations Hinges on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations, Palestine's delegate to the Arab League Mohamed
Sobeih said today the United States holds the key to the success
of the renewed talks.
</P>
<P>
Holding Washington responsible for the second round of talks
which will start tomorrow, Sobeih said that the outcome depends
basically on the U.S. pressure on Israel to settle outstanding
problems pertaining to security and settlement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross reportedly will hold talks with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat tomorrow and with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu for the preparation of trilateral
meeting between Palestinian chief negotiator Abu Mazen, Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy and Ross.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih, quoted by Egyptian Middle East News Agency, specified
two main conditions that will make Ross' mission in the region
successful.
</P>
<P>
First, the U.S. administration should be decisive with Israel
as regards implementing international resolutions and the
Palestinian-Israeli agreements signed. It should also maintain the
credibility as a witness to the signed agreements, Sobeih said.
</P>
<P>
Second, the Israeli leadership should be serious in realizing
peace and ending the "series of violence and war against Arabs in
Palestine and attempts to export terrorism abroad," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sobeih said Arafat held contacts with the U.S. officials a few
days ago and was assured that Washington's stance is unchanged
regarding the settlement issue which obstructs peace."
</P>
<P>
On September 29, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
after meeting with Mazen and Levy, announced in New York that the
Palestinian-Israeli negotiation will resume on October 6 in
Jerusalem and in Ramallah, West Bank with the participation of
Ross. Then the negotiations will be shifted to the U.S. on October
13.
</P>
<P>
The main topics for the coming negotiations are the security
cooperation, the definition of the time-out of Jewish
settlements, Israeli troop redeployment and ways for final-status
talks. 
</P>
