<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Chairman Urges Slow Changes of Banking Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the U.S. Federal
Reserve (Fed) Alan Greenspan pressed today for an overhaul of U.S.
federal banking laws but said that such change must be gradual to
protect the economy.
</P>
<P>
In remarks prepared for delivery at the annual convention of
the American Bankers Association in Boston, he called on "caution
and humility" in approaching banking reform.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of telecommunications and computer technology
has "lowered the costs, reduced the risks, and broadened the scope
of financial services," he said. "As a result, competitive
pressures in the financial services industry are probably greater
than ever before."
</P>
<P>
But Greenspan warned, "If we dramatically change the rules now
about banking and commerce... we may well end up doing more harm
than good." "And, as with all rule changes by government, we are
likely to find it impossible to correct our errors promptly, if at
all."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Fed chairman favors the dismantling of Depression Era
laws that bar banks from owning nonbanking corporations and
separate banking from insurance and stock underwriting.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. banking industry has long advocated such action so it
can better compete with other financial industries and with
foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. Congress has been struggling with a sweeping measure
approved earlier this year by the House Banking Committee. The
measure would allow banks to merge not only with brokerages,
insurers and other financial firms but also with commercial
companies.
</P>
<P>
Many U.S. banks already underwrite and deal in securities and
sell insurance and those with the resources and skill are
authorized to virtually match foreign bank competition abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
