<HEADLINE> France Considers US More Accommodating Over Total Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States wishes to choose
a "more quiet way" in settling its dispute with France over the 2
billion U.S. dollar deal signed last Sunday between the French oil
group Total and Iran, said a senior French official today.
</P>
<P>
French Delegate Minister for European Affairs Pierre Moscovici
said today in Luxembourg that European Union (EU) countries have
shown solidarity in the face of U.S. pressure over the Total deal.
</P>
<P>
The European commissioner in charge of trade relations, Leon
Brittan, today briefed officials of the 15 EU countries on the
on-going talks between Brussels and Washington on the U.S.
extra-territorial laws of the Helms-Burton Act and the D'Amato
Act.
</P>
<P>
Under the two acts, the United States bans all countries in the
world from dealing in large sums in the oil and hydrocarbon fields
with Iran and Libya, or having business with Cuba's state-owned
enterprises confiscated by the Cuban government from Cubans now
living in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Brittan told us that the American position is above all
accommodating that there was an anxiety to smooth the
differences," said Moscovici.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. daily Washington Post reported that the Clinton
administration has decided to hold off on sanctions against Total
to avert a trade war with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Rather than imposing sanctions on Total for signing a 2 billion
dollar contract to develop a natural gas field with Iran, the U.S.
government is seeking an agreement with the EU in which Washington
would scrap the threat of sanctions in exchange for increased
pressure on Iran to curb terrorism, said the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
