<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Blames Netanyahu for Peace Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today put the blame on Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
for failure to advance the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The Mideast peace process had made great strides until the
Likud government of Netanyahu came to power and announced that it
could not endorse the results of the agreements that its
predecessor, the Labor government had reached with the
Palestinians," Mubarak told the Egyptian Armed Forces Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt and the Palestinians could not accept such a thing
because it would mean that one of these days we would have to
accept their rejection of the peace treaty Israel signed with
Egypt," he said in an interview granted to the Arabic paper today
on the occasion of the 24th anniversary of the 1973 October War
victory against Israel. The interview was carried by the
Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been blocked for six
months over the Jewish state's building of settlements in the
occupied Arab lands. But the two sides agreed last week in New
York to restart formal talks this month
</P>
<P>
Mubarak stressed that only a just peace will bring stability
to all nations in the region, while the establishment of Jewish
settlement and the imposition of a status quo will never realize
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
"The only guarantee for security is to sustain the negotiating
process and make progress on the road to peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to reports on Egypt's growing military power and
its refusal to sign the chemical weapons non-proliferation
treaty, Mubarak said that Egypt will always be targeted because
of its central role.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed these claims as part of a political game of
exchanging pressure cards.
</P>
<P>
"These cards do not frighten me and we ourselves have our own
pressure cards that we can use when appropriate," said the
president.
</P>
<P>
Under the leadership of the late President Anwar Sadat,
Egyptian troops crossed the Suez Canal in October 1973 to recover
territory including the Sinai Peninsula lost in the "Six-Day War"
of June 1967 when Israel quickly defeated neighboring Arab states
including Egypt.
</P>
<P>
After 18 days of fighting, a cease-fire was arranged. In 1974
and 1975, the United States brokered disengagement agreements
between the two sides whereby Israel evacuated territory in Sinai
and Israeli and Egyptian forces were separated by a buffer zone
under the control of U.N. forces.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Israel signed a peace treaty in 1979, the first
between an Arab country and the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
