<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vocational Training Helpful to Employment: Eurostat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union hailed today
vocational training as the key to finding and keeping jobs by the
young in the European labor market.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg-based Eurostat, the statistics arm of the 15-nation
union, today published a joint report, the first ever
comprehensive collection of such information, from the union,
Eurostat and the European Center for the Development of Vocational
Training, which described education and vocational training as the
principal key to individual and collective development.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat figures showed that unemployment of 20- to
29-year-olds with additional vocational education and training is
less than half that of those with only basic education, or 11.5
percent compared with 23.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Surveys also found that 5.2 percent of those with only
compulsory education lost their jobs in 1995 whereas only 3.1
percent of those with additional vocational training lost theirs
in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Almost one third of young Europeans between the ages of 15 and
19 are engaged in initial vocational training, according to the
joint report which aims at providing essential data in support of
the EU employment strategy.
</P>
<P>
Luxembourg, that is serving the six-month rotating presidency
of the 15-nation union, takes employment as a major issue to
tackle under its leadership.
</P>
<P>
European Union-wide, unemployment hovered at 10.5 percent for
quite some time while Germany, France, Italy and Spain all posted
double-digit unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Growth Offers Opportunities to HK, Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The fast growth of China's
economy means a lot more opportunity ahead for Hong Kong and for
partners working with and through Hong Kong, a senior New Zealand
diplomat said here today.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has played a very active role, and an extremely large
role, in China's economic modernization drive since the late
1970s, New Zealand Consul-General in Hong Kong Carl Worker told a
trade mission briefing of the 28th General Assembly of the World
Trade Centers Association, prior to its opening ceremony here
today.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has been the leading source or channel for external
capital, technology and managerial and entrepreneurial inputs into
the Chinese economy throughout the reform era so far, Worker said
at the briefing on the International Perspective of Doing Business
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong naturally has earned big rewards. Just as China
would not be where it is today without Hong Kong, so without the
opportunities offered by China, Hong Kong would not look like it
does," Worker said in his speech titled "a New Zealand View
Through the Window of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"For New Zealand, Hong Kong has emerged as a top rank export
market. Globally, it is our sixth largest export market," after
Australia, Japan, the United States, Britain and the Republic of
Korea, and just ahead of China's mainland and Taiwan region,
Worker said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is New Zealand's fourth largest market for
elaborately transformed manufactured products, incorporating high
amounts of New Zealand value-added.
</P>
<P>
"It is our sixth largest supplier of foreign direct investment,
our eighth largest source of overseas visitors and our third
largest contributor of new migrants since the mid-80s," Worker
noted.
</P>
<P>
The biggest community of New Zealanders in Asia is based here
in Hong Kong, about 4,000 people. The New Zealand-Hong Kong
Business Association has the largest active membership of any New
Zealand offshore business association.
</P>
<P>
"My country therefore has a lot at stake in Hong Kong and its
future success," Worker said, adding "It is important to us as a
very special part of China."
</P>
<P>
New Zealand believes that China soon will be one of the most
important economies in the world and Hong Kong will continue to be
a very important factor in the continuing strengthening of New
Zealand's business relationship with China, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"We are enthusiastic and optimistic about Hong Kong's
opportunities, and about New Zealand's opportunities in and
through Hong Kong," he declared.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
