<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul, Washington to Hold Talks on Dumping Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea said today it will
hold another round of talks with the United States over
Washington's anti-dumping duty on its color TVs and computer
memory chips.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy said
they are ready to take the dispute to the World Trade Organization
(WTO) if the U.S. fails to revoke its tariffs in the talks in
Geneva on Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries failed to agree on the penalties at their
first meeting in August.
</P>
<P>
South Korea filed a complaint on August with the WTO's dispute
settlement body after the United States decided in July to
preserve anti-dumping sanctions against South Korea's 16-megabyte
dynamic random access memory, or DRAM, chips, which can enhance
computers' performance in running various programs.
</P>
<P>
Washington has imposed the penalties since 1993, accusing South
Korea of illegally lowering prices to expand market share in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department said in July's ruling that the
penalties on South Korean computer chips must be kept because of
possible dumping by South Korean companies in the future -- a
decision that South Korea says has violated WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
Computer memory chips are South Korea's key export items. South
Korea and Japan each provide 40 percent of the world's supply of
DRAM chips.
</P>
<P>
South Korea also has filed in July a similar complaint with
the WTO against U.S. anti-dumping duty on its color TVs.
</P>
<P>
South Korean officials said their country has not dumped their
color TVs in the U.S. market since 1984 and even suspended their
shipments completely during the past seven years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
