<HEADLINE> 10 War Crimes Suspects Surrender to UN Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Ten Bosnian Croat war crimes
suspects today surrendered themselves to The Hague-based
International Criminal Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia (ICTY) for
trial.
</P>
<P>
The suspects, including the most wanted, Dario Kordic, have
arrived in the Netherlands after agreeing to hand themselves over
for trial to the U.N. war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to turn themselves in after the United Nations
tribunal guaranteed them a quick and fair trial.
</P>
<P>
Kordic was quoted as saying before leaving Croatia that the
group was departing "with a clear conscience before God and the
Croatian people in order to prove its innocence."
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana
said that the surrender of war crimes suspects was an important
step that demonstrated that the international community is
determined to see that justice and the rule of law prevail in the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"I renew my call to all the parties to implement fully their
obligations under the (Dayton) peace agreement and to extend their
complete cooperation to the ICTY in the investigation and
prosecution of war crimes," Solana said.
</P>
<P>
War crimes suspects have been a thorny issue for the NATO-led
multinational Stabilization Force (SFOR). Discussions were
underway whether and how to round up indicted war criminals for
trials so as to help establish a security environment in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
There are also indicted war criminals among Bosnian Serbs who
were blamed for most of the ethnic cleansing during the four-year
civil war in the former Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
