<HEADLINE> HK Staying the Course, U.S. Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is staying the
course in terms of remaining a free and open society during the
first 100 post-handover days, which sets a fine tune for the
future, visiting U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to say that, in speaking with Hong Kong's
leadership, it appears that Hong Kong is staying the course in
terms of remaining a free and open society," Daley told a luncheon
hosted by the American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong, the
largest American chamber outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
"In the United States, we closely scrutinize the first 100 days
of any new administration. Many say that the first 100 days set
the tone for the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will mark its first 100 days since the handover later
this week, on October 8.
</P>
<P>
Daley is on his first official visit to the Island of Lights
and he will be traveling to Beijing for the 11th session of the
U.S.-China Joint Commission on Commerce and Trade which he
co-chairs with his Chinese counterpart, Wu Yi.
</P>
<P>
He met with Hong Kong's Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa,
Administrative Secretary Anson Chan and Secretary for Trade and
Industry Denise Yue this morning.
</P>
<P>
"I said (to them) it is of the utmost importance for our
bilateral relationship that Hong Kong continues to be Hong Kong.
It must remain a free and open society and a stable economy."
</P>
<P>
Daley summarized U.S. presence in the city, noting that some
1,100 U.S. businesses are represented here and more than 400 of
them maintain regional headquarters; more than 50,000 U.S.
citizens live here, a number that has doubled in five years; and
U.S. investment here continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. interests in Hong Kong have always been strong... We look
forward to Hong Kong's continued success as a Special
Administrative Region of China with a high degree of autonomy."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary spoke highly of Hong Kong's exemplary
anti-corruption record, saying the Independent Commission Against
Corruption is of world renown.
</P>
<P>
But concerns are there too, he noted. First is intellectual
property rights and second is export controls, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
