<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Strikes Pact With London Club on Soviet Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the London Club of
creditor banks signed an agreement here today on rescheduling the
debts inherited by Russia from the former Soviet Union, the
Interfax news service reported.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the agreement allows Russia, which took on all
Soviet foreign debts after the disintegration of the former Soviet
Union in 1991, to pay off some 33 billion U.S. dollars within 25
years.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Russia's Vneshekonombank, which has
represented Russia during marathon debt talks with the London Club
since December 1992, will issue interest-bearing bonds to be
issued on the Luxembourg stock exchange. The bonds will be
circulated both in and outside Russia.
</P>
<P>
On December 2, 1997, the creditors will be repaid for the first
time in five years when they obtain part of the owed interest
equivalent to more than 3 billion dollars, and receive bonds worth
the unpaid part of the interest, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
