<HEADLINE> France Raps "Suspension" of UNHCR Activities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- France today criticized the
"suspension" by the government of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) of the activities by the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) in the DRC as "a setback for human rights."
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said that
France deplores the decision by Kinshasa to drive the staff out of
the UNHCR as well as its intention to pressure other humanitarian
organizations to leave the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in the North Kivu region remains difficult and
confusing and knows still violent inter-ethnic confrontations. The
presence of humanitarian organizations contributes to alleviating
the sufferings of the civil population," said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He said that the newest decision by Kinshasa took place after
the DRC authorities asked the U.N. to withdraw an investigation
team on the massacre of Hutu refugees in the eastern DRC.
</P>
<P>
DRC Interior Minister Mwenze Kongola said Sunday in Kinshasa
that his government decided to "suspend" the activities of the
UNHCR in the North and South Kivu regions of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He accused the UNHCR of "inciting Rwandan refugees who had
returned to their country to return" to the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He also asked other humanitarian organizations "whose
activities are no longer useful" to quit the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
