<HEADLINE> International Maritime Conference Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The international shipping
conference, Maritime Cyprus 1997, opened here today with the
participation of more than 1,000 delegates from over 30
countries.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, acting President of the
Republic of Cyprus, House President Spyros Kyprianou said Cyprus
is an important shipping center and would continue to develop as
such through cooperation of state and private initiatives.
</P>
<P>
"The international standards which we wish to ensure for our
shipping will be further strengthened by the legal framework of
the European Union, of which Cyprus aspires to become a full
member soon," Kyprianou added.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Minister of Communications and works Leontios
Ierodiakonou also stressed at the meeting that the Cypriot
government is committed to enhancing the quality of ships flying
the Cyprus flag and is deeply concerned about safety and the
protection of environment.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that Turkey has unilaterally
introduced restrictive measures against Cyprus ships. "This is a
dangerous precedent and affects international trade and
transport", the minister warned.
</P>
<P>
He said that every effort should be made to persuade Turkey to
abandon this unacceptable behaviour.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the three-day conference is "A New Era in
Shipping," which will focus on new principles and targets that
will be adopted by the international shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government is keen to diversify the island's
sources of income, and the convening of the conference here has
helped attract the shipping world's attention to the country's
reliable infrastructure, communications, services sector and a
highly professional and skilled workforce.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ranks fifth on the list of the world's shipping
powers, with 2,640 vessels flying the Cypriot flag, whose tonnage
totals 24.5 million.
</P>
<P>
The island's revenues from its merchant shipping reaches 50
million Cyprus pounds (100 million U.S. dollars) a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Airlines Decides to Increase Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 6 (Xinhua)-- Indian Airlines (IA) today
decided to increase its fares from October 15 to obtain additional
revenue to offset the rising input costs in various areas of
operations, an IA spokesman said here.
</P>
<P>
While the fare hike on short haul sectors up to 700 kilometers
will be 14 percent, the increase on long haul routes above 700
kilometers will be 10.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The decision to increase fares was approved by the common Board
of Directors of IA and Air India (AI).
</P>
<P>
"The increase in fares is only to offset the increases in the
cost of operations during 1996-97 and most of the input costs were
beyond the control of the airlines," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to another report, the country's Railway Ministry
today decided not to raise passenger fares as reported earlier.
</P>
<P>
But the cost of coal freight will go up by 4 percent while
freight charges on food grains, pulses and sugar will jump by 5
percent following partial withdrawal of freight exemption on
certain essential commodities of mass consumption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
