<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Calls for Greenhouse Gas Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Japanese government today put
forth a proposal for industrial countries to reduce greenhouse gas
emissions by an average of 5 percent from 1990 level during the
year of 2008 to 2012.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would allow every industrial country to set its
own target on the basis of one of the three indexes -- greenhouse
gas emissions related to gross domestic product (GDP) in 1990,
per-capita gas emissions in 1990, and population growth between
1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
This would put Japan's target at about 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
"With this proposal as the basis for discussion, we will make
efforts to see a fair and attainable international agreement
early," a Japanese top government spokesman said, referring to the
United Nations (UN) conference on climate change to be hosted by
Japan in Kyoto from December 1 to 10.
</P>
<P>
The proposal also calls for the right for industrial nations to
trade emissions quotas with other countries under certain
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries will not be asked to undertake greenhouse
gas emissions cut obligation at the Kyoto Conference, but Japan is
ready to strengthen its financial and technology cooperation with
developing countries to help them make progress in the field, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Greenhouse gases, which include carbon dioxide, methane and
nitrous oxide, are blamed for global warming.
</P>
<P>
Japan will try to win approval for its proposal for the Kyoto
meeting at the next round of preparatory talks in Bonn beginning
October 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Minister Sees Bright Future for Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- China's Minister for Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu Yi today presented a bright
picture of the future of China's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
"China's trade volume is expected to reach 400 billion
U.S. dollars in the year 2000, which means the country will
provide the world with a market as big as 700 billion dollars in
the next four years," she said here in a keynote speech to the
opening ceremony of the 28th General Assembly of the World Trade
Centers Association, a non-governmental organization for the
promotion of world trade.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that during the 19 years following the
introduction of the reform and opening-up policy, China's foreign
trade has been expanding at an average 16.5 percent per annum,
higher than the annual economic growth which stands at roughly 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
The growth in foreign trade is also eight percentage points
higher than the expansion of global trade as a whole, Wu added.
</P>
<P>
In addition, China has made great achievements in using foreign
investment and in other fields of economic cooperation, she said.
</P>
<P>
"But China, as a developing country with a huge population of
1.2 billion, still has an imbalanced economic development, with 58
million of its people living in poverty. Therefore it still has a
long way to go in its economic development."
</P>
<P>
"According to China's Ninth Five-Year Plan and an outline of
long-term objectives for 2010, China will maintain an economic
growth of 8-9 percent in the next few years and 7 percent in the
first decade of next century," she said.
</P>
<P>
China can not achieve development without the world and vice
versa, she said. China welcomes friends in other countries to
invest in it and participate in fair competition on Chinese market
and furthermore, it attaches great importance to economic and
technological cooperation with all other countries and regions in
the world on the basis of equality and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
The just-concluded 15th National Congress of the Communist
Party of China worked out a blueprint for the future development
of China, which will open even wider to the rest of the world, Wu
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the country's announcement just a few days ago to
further lower its tariff level to 17 percent, the minister said
that so far China has not only reduced its tariff by 60 percent
since 1993, but also made a commitment to the world to bring down
its tariff level to the average of developing countries by the end
of the century.
</P>
<P>
This fully demonstrates China's determination and confidence in
participating in international competition and cooperation, Wu
said, adding that China will adopt much more preferential policies
for high-tech equipment and advanced technology entering China.
</P>
</TEXT>
