<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses Iran of Plotting Attack in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has accused Iran of sending
intelligence agents to carry out an attack on the office of World
Health Organization (WHO) in Baghdad, Iraqi News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
INA said in a report that interrogation of the arrested during
the attack revealed that the four assailants were sent by Iran's
intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
Four gunmen raided the WHO's headquarters here on Saturday
throwing grenades and firing bullets, destroying one vehicle and
damaging two others in the compound, said Eric Falt, a spokesman
of the WHO headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The attack on the building occurred when there were no staffers,
without injuring a person, said Falt. The Iraqi army arrested one
of the gunmen, but the three others escaped, he added, quoted by
INA.
</P>
<P>
According to INA, the arrested attacker, belonging to an
Iranian community used to reside in Iraq, was deported in
1983. INA said he "infiltrated the Iraqi territory to serve the
Iranian intelligence purposes."
</P>
<P>
Interrogation is under way in order for him to "expose the aim
of this cowardly attack," INA said.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq have been bitter enemies who fought an eight year
war from 1980 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
The WHO headquarters in Baghdad is responsible for distributing
food and medicine in northern and southern Iraq under the
oil-for-food program signed between Iraq and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The U.N.'s humanitarian coordinator in Baghdad, Denis Halliday,
condemned the attack which is the first ever at a U.N. building in
Iraq, said INA.
</P>
<P>
"It is the Iraqi government's responsibility to protect U.N.
personnel and property against any harm," said the Halliday,
demanding for a meeting with senior Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under harsh U.N. economic sanctions since its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. But the oil-for-food deal allows Iraq to
sell 2 billion dollars worth of oil every six months since
December 1996 to buy food and medicine Iraq urgently needs under
close U.N. supervision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
