<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Biochemist Wins 1997 Nobel Medicine Prize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 6 (Xinhua)-- U.S. biochemist Stanley B.
Prusiner today was awarded the 1997 Nobel Medicine Prize for his
discovery of prion -- a disease-causing agent like bacteria or
viruses, said the Nobel Assembly at the Sweden's Karolinska
Institute.
</P>
<P>
The assembly said that Prusiner's discovery would help key
insights into dementia-related diseases and help the world
understand more about Alzheimer's and Mad Cow Disease.
</P>
<P>
"Prusiner's discovery provides important insights that may
furnish the basis to understand the biological mechanisms
underlying other types of dementia-related diseases, for example
Alzheimer's disease, and establishes a foundation for drug
development and new types of medical treatment strategies," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Prions exist normally as innocuous cellular proteins, however,
they possess an innate capacity to convert their structures into
highly stable conformations that ultimately result in the
formation of harmful particles, which can cause disease and death
of humans and animals. The assembly said Prusiner has solved the
riddle of the prison's prosperities.
</P>
<P>
Some prion diseases such as Mad Cow disease and Alzheimer's are
attaining general attention around the world.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Prusiner, born in 1942, is now professor of neurology,
of virology in residence and of biochemistry at the California
University in San Francisco. He began his research work in 1972
after one of his patients died of dementia resulting from
Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samsung Develops World's Fastest 4M SRAM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Samsung Electronics
Co. LTD. announced today its completion of developing an
asynchronous 4M "fast" SRAM (static random-access memory), which
operates more quickly than any other high-capacity SRAM available.
</P>
<P>
Produced through the complementary metal oxide semiconductor
(CMOS) processing, the new device can process data in just 10
nanoseconds (one nanosecond is one-billionth of a second), which
reduces manufacturing time and unit costs. As a result, price
competitive power is enhanced, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Conventional SRAMs operate on 10 milliamperes of standby
current, while the new Samsung "fast" SRAM requires only 1
milliampere, greatly reducing the possibility of power consumption.
</P>
<P>
In addition, other new functions like the Support Data
Retention Application can prevent noise generated on the circuit
periphery. Thus, fewer errors are made during data transmission -
generally caused by momentary drops in electrical signal voltage
due to noise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
