<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thriving Island City Maintains Good Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Haikou, capital city of the south
China island province of Hainan, has kept the title of China's
cleanest city for seven years, thanks to its efforts in
environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the city environmental protection department said
that despite its burgeoning economy, the city authorities have
always attached the utmost importance to preserving a good
environment since the establishment of Hainan province in 1990,
which is also China's largest special economy zone.
</P>
<P>
Back in 1992 when the local economy, especially real estates,
was most brisk, the city authorities designated 71.3 ha of land
along the coast where the land price is the highest for the
building of a park.
</P>
<P>
Other parks were also built elsewhere in the city, while trees
have been planted along 136 streets and avenues with a total
length of 1,330 km. At present the city's vegetation has reached
39 percent.
</P>
<P>
Disposal of waste water is another thorny problem in keeping a
good environment. Haikou has started building a modern disposal
project with a capacity of treating 300,000 tons of waste water a
day. The overall cost of the project is estimated at 500 million
yuan (about 60 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Over the past seven years, Haikou has spent a total of 1.2
billion yuan (about 144 million US dollars) in building
flood-control and drainage facilities, a sum 40 times that spent
during the 38 years before the establishment of Hainan province.
</P>
<P>
The city has also closed a number of inefficient and heavily
polluting plants, and spread the use of pipeline and liquified
gas, making the city virtually free of smog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
