<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China's Magnificent Glacier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A new glacier, which sits at the
southernmost latitude of any glacier is China, was recently
discovered in southwest China's Yunnan Province at an elevation of
only 2,700 meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The glacier is located in Deqen County at 28 degrees north
latitude.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the Mingyoungqia Glacier, which stretches some
eight km. and is 30 meters thick, has been formed by ice and snow
avalanches from the snow-capped Meili Mountain.
</P>
<P>
The face of the glacier tongues extends to some 2,600 meters
above sea level, with sun refraction adding a greenish cast to ice
channels and small blocks dotting the sparkling crystal clear ice
mass.
</P>
<P>
Primeval forests line both sides of the glacier, and walnut and
fruit trees grow within 200 meters of the ice. Local farmers also
note that cabbages, cucumbers, onions and various other vegetables
can easily be grown in the area.
</P>
<P>
The scenery around the glacier reminds people of "Shangri-la"
American author James Hilton described in his work entitled "Lost
Horizon". Kagbo Peak, the highest peak on Meili Mountain,
resembled the pyramidal mentioned in Hilton's novel.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 villagers living near the glacier live in virtual
isolation surrounded by the mountains and the Lancang River. The
villagers lead a life far from the turmoil of the world.
</P>
<P>
Another aspect similar to Hilton's novel rests with the fact
that numerous air crashes have been reported in the vicinity of
the glacier.
</P>
<P>
The brick and tile ruins of a church, reportedly built some 600
years ago by a British missionary, are found in close proximity to
the glacier, and tiles can still be found.
</P>
<P>
The glacier is rapidly becoming a new tourist attraction
despite the lack of highway access. Visitors ride horses to the
nearby village where they can enjoy Tibetan food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0076 </DOCNO>
