<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Ice Mortars Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nine "stone cauldrons"
in Fengning county in north China's Hebei
province have turned out to be rare ice mortars formed more than
one million years ago.
</P>
<P>
They were formed by melting water at the bottom of a glacier,
which swirls and carries stone, abrading the granite structure
to form a spiral-shaped pit, or ice mortar.
</P>
<P>
These ice mortars were discovered in early August by three
professors from the
Chinese Academy of Geological Sciences on Mount Lhama in Fengning
county, who said this is strong evidence of the existance of
glaciers perhaps as big as the ice sheet of Antarctica or
Greenland.
</P>
<P>
Other ice mortars in the world are thought to have been formed
at a much later period. Ordinary ice mortars are generally found
at the foot of a mountain, but the Fengning mortars were on a
ridge. They are 1 to 3 meters in diameter and 0.3 to 1.5 meters
deep. Some scientists think they may be the first mortars in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The discovery is important for research on global climates,
environmental evolution, and climatic variation, as well as for
the study of the origin of human beings and other sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
