<HEADLINE> Riley Swims Third-fastest Time in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- World champion Samantha Riley
swam the third fastest time in history to win the women's 100
meters breaststroke final at the Australian world championships
trials in Brisbane on Monday.
</P>
<P>
By clocking one minute 7.66 seconds, Riley remained a title
contender at the world championships which will be held in western
Australian city of Perth from January 8 to 18 next year.
</P>
<P>
South African Penny Heyns, who set the world record of 1:07.02
at last year's Atlanta Olympic Games, has swum the two fastest
breaststroke times.
</P>
<P>
Riley's swim was the fastest in the world this year and sliced
0.03 seconds off the Australian record, which she set at the 1994
Worlds.
</P>
<P>
Riley was followed by Helen Denham in 1:08.96.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta Olympic butterfly champion Susie O'Neill snatched the
women's 200 meters freestyle final after beating Perth teenager
Julia Greville in the home stretch.
</P>
<P>
Meredith Smith won the women's 50 meters backstroke final by
touching home in 29.72 seconds.  Bianca Jones was second in 30.33.
</P>
<P>
Matt Welsh broke an Australian record as he timed 26.12 seconds
in the men's 50 meters backstroke final where Joshua Watson came
second in 26.33.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Dunn won the men's 400 meters individual medley in
4:19.10 and Trent Steed finished runner-up in 4:22.62. 
