<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Formulate Malaria Control Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government
decided to formulate a national malaria control policy, reported
local daily "The New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
The policy will ensure availability of adequate resources to
all government facilities, the paper said, adding that it will
also enable proper management of people with malaria.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the policy, the public will be
educated on preventive measures, which include recognizing
malaria, treating it and raising awareness about dangerous
practices of self medication and failure to comply with
treatment.
</P>
<P>
The policy, the paper said, will stress district based
activities to allow malaria control to be integrated into primary
health care within the framework of the decentralization of
health services.
</P>
<P>
Malaria is still the number one killer disease in most
districts in Uganda. It is responsible for 25 percent of
out-patient visits, 14 percent of hospital in-patient deaths and 20
percent of hospital admission in government facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan Ministry of Health spends over 27 million U.S.
Dollars annually for treatment of sanitation-related diseases
including malaria.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the situation of prevalence of malaria has
worsened due to the collapse of health and other social services
to handle it.
</P>
<P>
Mismanagement of malaria cases both by the patients themselves
and by the health care providers has also led to drug resistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
