<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Rejects Japan's Greenhouse Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia found itself more
isolated internationally today as Prime Minister John Howard
rejected Japan's proposed greenhouse gas emission plan.
</P>
<P>
Australia would not sign an international climate change treaty
which was unfair and failed to take into account the country's
reliance on fossil fuels, Howard said tonight.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the Australian Chamber of Manufacturers in
Melbourne, Howard rejected Japan's proposal for industrialized
countries to cut by 5 percent by 2012 the 1990 levels of
greenhouse gas emissions, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, unveiled in Tokyo today, is well below the
European Union's push for a blanket 15-percent cut in emissions
from the 1990 levels by 2010 for developed countries.
</P>
<P>
Howard, who has been lobbying heavily for support for
Australia's position from his counterparts of the United States
and Japan during the past several months, admitted that Australia
faces a tough task selling its plan for greenhouse gas emission
targets, which would be settled at a major climate change summit
in Japan in December.
</P>
<P>
The United States has yet to announce its greenhouse reduction
plan.
</P>
<P>
Howard's comments were also echoed today by Environment
Minister Robert Hill, who remains cautiously optimistic that
Australia would continue to negotiate to achieve a "good outcome."
</P>
<P>
Australia has argued that the outcome should include developing
countries and that targets should take into account each country's
different economic circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"If it was a figure that would simply result in tens of
thousands, or perhaps by some of the figures hundreds of thousands
of job losses to Australia, then we obviously wouldn't be party to
such an agreement," Hill said on a national radio today.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Japanese proposal would force Australia to
reduce its emissions by 2 to 3 percent from the 1990 levels, which
he said "would have a devastating effect on the Australian
economy."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
