<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel-Jordan Ties Suffer Damages: Ex-ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The botched attack in Jordan
on a Hamas leader by suspected Israeli secret agents has dealt a
serious blow to Israeli-Jordanian relations, said Shimon Shamir,
former Israeli ambassador to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Jerusalem Post newspaper, Shamir said the
failed operation would expose Jordanian government to accusations
from opponents and restrict it from cooperating with Israel.
</P>
<P>
On September 25, two suspected agents of Israel's intelligence
service Mossad carrying forged Canadian passports, attacked Hamas
leader Khalid Mashiel and injected a toxic substance into his
left ear in Amman. The assailants were detained by Jordanian
police.
</P>
<P>
Shamir blamed the bad timing of the incident as Jordan's
parliamentary elections are only one month away and "the
Jordanian government is now in a serious situation of competition
with the Islamist opposition."
</P>
<P>
"This is the biggest domestic issue at the moment," said
Shamir, who is considered a leading expert on Middle East affairs
in general and Jordanian-Israeli relations in particular.
</P>
<P>
The Islamists are "mounting a great challenge to the
legitimacy of the parliament and Jordan's political system," and
they "would have used the matter to undermine the peace accord by
accusing Israel of continuing to act in a high-handed manner in
Jordan itself," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The damage would have been enormous," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the fallout and help repair the damage to
Israeli-Jordanian relations, Shamir said "what should be done now
within the parameters of the Israeli domestic political system is
that first the Israeli policy must demonstrate that when it makes
a mistake it has a machinery for correcting it."
</P>
<P>
"The first action should be to establish who is responsible
and draw the necessary conclusions from that. This would show
the outside world that we are human and make mistakes and may
misunderstand things, but we have a mechanism to repair it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Once we have demonstrated that, we should start the long and
difficult work of damage control and rebuilding confidence," he
said. "This cannot be achieved in one day and I'm afraid will be
long process," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
