<HEADLINE> Veld Fire Destroys Grazing Land, Kills Livestock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 hectares
of grazing land and hundreds of head of livestock have been
destroyed by a four-day veld fire which spread to 16 farms in the
Eastern Cape Province, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The South African Press Association reported today that the
fire, believed to have been started by lightning on Thursday, was
still burning in some areas on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Local police and the army set up a joint operations command to
help fight the flames.
</P>
<P>
The fire had caused considerable damage to domestic stock and
the environment, a local police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Police Senior Superintendent Dries Trollip, who was monitoring
the situation, said about 150 sheep had been killed in the
Cradock area alone.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers slept in the bush, afraid that the fire, which
was spreading rapidly by strong winds, might spread to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
Roland Kroon, chairman of a farmers' association, said the
fire, if uncurbed, may bring about big trouble for the local
farmers, most of whom are wool farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
