<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Not to Step Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said today that he is not stepping down as prime
minister amid what he says is a definite attempt by the foreign
media and fund managers to "get rid" of him.
</P>
<P>
"There is definitely an attempt by certain foreign media and
fund managers to get rid of me," he told reporters upon his return
from a 12-day tour of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that the foreign media were being controlled by
people with vested interest, adding that the rumors of his
resignation were cooked up and he believed that the rumors would
persist because this was the aim of the currency traders.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir denied that his statements against currency
manipulators had caused Malaysia's ringgit to fall further.
</P>
<P>
He said that other countries, whose leaders did not say
anything, also saw their currencies fall even further.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia alone did not suffer from the currency and
stock market crisis but its ASEAN counterparts such as Indonesia,
the Philippines and Thailand, were also severely affected.
</P>
<P>
Following speculative attacks against ASEAN currencies starting
with the Thai baht, three other currencies -- the ringgit,
Indonesia's rupiah and the Philippines' peso -- also depreciated
significantly against major currencies.
</P>
<P>
There were foreign elements out to destroy Malaysia's economy
as well as that of the ASEAN region, he said, adding foreign
elements were jealous of ASEAN's dynamic economic growth which was
why they were probably be "full of glee" now that these economies
were going through crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said that there was no justification for these economies to
be attacked when other countries were in far worse economic
situations.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that such manipulative attacks "are not a passing
thing. It is a serious thing."
</P>
<P>
On allegations that his statements had pressured the ringgit
further down, he said that in the first place when the currency
crisis broke out, he abstained from saying anything, but then, the
ringgit kept on falling due to the continued manipulative attacks,
that was why he had to speak up.
</P>
<P>
The ringgit depreciated about 34 percent in the past two
months. The local unit closed today at 3.3650/50 against the U.S.
dollar in comparison with 2.5200 in early July.
</P>
<P>
Giving an assurance that the current economic problems facing
Malaysia will be overcome, Mahathir called on Malaysians to pull
themselves together to come out of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ways and means would be devised to tackle the current
weaknesses in the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that it was ironic that while Malaysia's
fundamentals were good such as its low inflation rate, its
currency was battered while currencies of other countries, whose
fundamentals were weak and inflation rates were over a thousand
percent, did not depreciate at all.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir welcomed Japan's pledge to help ASEAN countries tackle
current account deficit woes.
</P>
<P>
Japan has offered measures to raise its imports from ASEAN
countries by ensuring the region's trade transactions with
Japanese firms.
</P>
<P>
Japan is expected to provide details of its pledge to help
ASEAN at the forthcoming ASEAN Economic Ministers' Meeting (AEM)
to be held here next week.
</P>
<P>
During his Latin America tour, Mahathir, accompanied by an
official delegation including Works Minister S. Samy Vellu and a
high-powered business group, visited Cuba, Chile, Uruguay and
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The tour has been described as "successful". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
