<HEADLINE> Entry of Jeep Cherokee Stiffens Car Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The recent launch in Kenya of
Jeep Cherokee has stiffened competition in an already tight car
market, The East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The four-wheel-drive jeep manufactured by the Chrysler
Corporation entered the Kenyan market with an aim to squzee into
a narrow but growing niche at the top end of the market, the weekly paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the luxury vehicle in Kenya signals a
significant interests in the East Africa market by the third
largest American auto-maker. Prior to Chryler, another two U.S.
motor manufacturers
General Motors and Ford re-entered the east African nation early
this year.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures from the Kenya motor industry indicate a
growing demand for luxury four-wheel-drive cars, increasing from
510 assorted models in 1994 to 837 up to August 1997.
</P>
<P>
Leading sales in August were: Land Rover Discovery (238
units), Isuzu Trooper (80 units), Mitsubishi Pajero (52 units),
range Rover (18 units) and Nissan Patrol (10 units).
</P>
<P>
More than 100 units of Jeep Cherokee were imported for the
trial runs in mid-September and 20 had already been sold, the
paper said, adding that Chrysler had planned to open a
full-fledged franchise in Kenya next year after the present sales
trials.
</P>
<P>
The new jeep, marketed internationally as the king of the off
road, will be followed by the Jeep Grand Cherokee and the Jeep
Wrangler models.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a sales manager as predicting that
established dealers would have an edge in the sales battle owing
to their countrywide service network.
</P>
<P>
The manager pointed out that "a buyer mainly goes for a model
that can be serviced at his convenience in any part of the
country without having to come back to Nairobi."
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 3,659 car units have been sold this year
with luxury four-wheelers representing 21 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
