<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Remains Good Place for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is still a good
place to do business after the handover while its status as a
global trading center is becoming even more important thanks to
its increasing economic integration with China's interior, a
local business organization said today.
</P>
<P>
Active members from the Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce
briefed representatives attending the 28th World Trade Centers
Association's General Assembly here on the latest development of
Hong Kong's trade and economy.
</P>
<P>
"People in Hong Kong have confidence in the future," Paul
Cheng, former chairman of the chamber, said. "We have all freedom
we want" after July 1.
</P>
<P>
He reassured the international audience that on establishing
regional headquarters, Hong Kong beats Tokyo and Singapore, her
two closest competitors in the Asia-Pacific region, thanks to her
rule of law, fine infrastructure, level playing field and language
capacity.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that foreign investors interested in entering
China's interior work through Hong Kong companies as local
companies have abundant experience in doing business in the
interior.
</P>
<P>
His points of view were echoed by Denis Lee, managing director
of Kingscore Industrial Ltd., a small business, and Ms Lily
Chiang, executive director of Chen Hsong Holdings Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will continue to be a good place to invest or do
business," Lee said. By establishing offices in Hong Kong,
overseas company will also be well placed to tap the vast market
of China's interior, he added.
</P>
<P>
China's interior has become a highly influential factor in Hong
Kong's economic growth, Lee noted. Now the Chinese interior is the
largest trading partner of Hong Kong while Hong Kong is the
largest external investor in China's interior, he said.
</P>
<P>
"For three months till now as a Special Administrative Region
(SAR) of China, it is business as usual for Hong Kong," he told
the international trading and commerce sector.
</P>
<P>
The chamber's forecast for growth of 1997 and through to 2000
is between 5-6 percent, suggesting the economy is moving smoothly
through the transition period and into the new decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lily Chiang, in her speech focusing on local manufacturing
sector, described the relationship between China's interior and
Hong Kong as a "lip and teeth" one.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1980s, Hong Kong entrepreneurs have been
relocating their business in South China and even northern parts
of the interior, taking advantage of lower land and labor costs
there, she said.
</P>
<P>
Chiang forecast the next century to be "a century of China",
and stated that Hong Kong is a window of China and its importance
to China is unquestionable.
</P>
<P>
With a more proactive approach of the SAR government in
industrial development as well as the expected benefit from the
economic integration between China's interior and Hong Kong, the
golden opportunity of doing business in Hong Kong has been
upgraded to the diamond opportunity.
</P>
<P>
For those who have yet to enter the market of the Chinese
interior, the young entrepreneur gave her advice that Hong Kong be
 used as a springboard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
