<HEADLINE> HKSAR Official Outlines Achievements of government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Administrative Secretary
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), Anson Chan,
today outlined major achievements of the local government in the
past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
She also praised the work of all the government staff in the
transition period and stressed that efforts made by the government
had provided conditions for the smooth return of Hong Kong to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here this afternoon, Chan briefed
reporters on her "Progress Report," or named "The 1997 Policy
Address," which details achievements of outstanding undertakings
made by the government's 19 departments.
</P>
<P>
The 263-page report was issued and became available to the
public immediately after the news conference.
</P>
<P>
"In the past year, we have worked on a total of 830 pledges,"
Chan said. "The government is well on target in meeting 783 of
these commitments, or 94 percent of the total."
</P>
<P>
According to her:
</P>
<P>
-- The government has already completed in full the
implementation of 363 commitments;
</P>
<P>
-- It continues to honor 137 commitments which are ongoing,
achieving substantial progress in areas such as social welfare,
health, education, housing and protection of the environment;
</P>
<P>
-- It is on schedule in implementing further 248 commitments;
</P>
<P>
-- It is actively reviewing 17 commitments where the programs
may have to be adjusted to take account of the changing needs of
the community, the need for further discussion with the
legislature, the need to take account of public consultation or
because of revisions to past policies.
</P>
<P>
However, "we have encountered some slippage but expect to meet
our overall targets on 18 commitments," and "there are also 47
undertakings, or 6 percent of the total, we are behind schedule,"
she noted.
</P>
<P>
"Our report identifies clearly those undertakings which are
behind schedule and explains the reasons for the shortfalls or
delays," Chan said. "We will take all possible measures to catch
up with the original targets."
</P>
<P>
She emphasized that the SAR government is "an open and
accountable government," noting that it will set out its
objectives and programs and report on their progress annually
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Executive of the Hong Kong SAR, Tung Chee Hwa, will
deliver his inaugural policy speech Wednesday, in which he is
expected to announce tasks and priorities for the SAR government
in the following year, Chan told reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
