<HEADLINE> HK, US Agree to Cooperate on Strategic Commodities Trade Controls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and the United
States agreed here today to closer cooperation on strategic
commodities trade controls, the American Consulate General
announced.
</P>
<P>
Visiting U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley and Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region Secretary for Trade and Industry
Denise Yue held discussions this morning, according to a press
release from the consulate general.
</P>
<P>
A Minute of Discussions reaffirms the U.S. supportive policy
with Hong Kong on trade in strategic commodities, which gives Hong
Kong broad access to U.S. goods and technologies, and provides for
regular meetings on strategic commodities trade controls.
</P>
<P>
It calls for broadened sharing of information on these controls
and related enforcement matters.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Daley said, "I am pleased with Hong Kong's efforts in
maintaining effective controls and continued cooperation on trade
in strategic commodities. This Minute of Discussions underscores
Hong Kong's commitment to maintain the integrity of its controls.
It supports our policy of continuing to give Hong Kong broad
access to U.S. goods and technology."
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the U.S. continued supportive policy toward Hong Kong
over trade in strategic commodities, Secretary Yue said, "It is in
Hong Kong's own economic and commercial interests to maintain
effective controls over trade in strategic commodities."
</P>
<P>
"Only by doing so can we ensure our free access to
sophisticated goods and technologies which are essential for Hong
Kong's economic development," she said.
</P>
<P>
She stated, "We are committed to practicing the highest
standards of controls and enforce our laws fully. We look forward
to receiving continued support from our trading partners."
</P>
</TEXT>
