<HEADLINE> Britain Lifts Ban on Nigerian Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom Civil Aviation
Authorities has unconditionally lifted the ban it has imposed on
Nigerian-registered aircrafts from flying into its airspace,
press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Andy Stern, the General Manager of the British Airways, West
Africa, was quoted as saying in Lagos Sunday that British
Department of Transport informed the decision to the Nigerian
side some time ago, through a letter to the British High
Commission in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Minister of Aviation, Air Commander Ita Udo-Imeh,
however, on September 25 denied of being aware of the decision,
adding that if there was such a development, his ministry would
be the first to break the news.
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, officials of the British Airways
are daily making inquiries on the normalization of flights
between the countries.
</P>
<P>
"We await his (the minister's) response and remain keen to
start flying again with our traditional good value for money,
fares and high quality services," said Andy Stern.
</P>
<P>
The British ban on Nigerian airplanes, which was imposed on
May 15 for safety reasons, was immediately revenged by a similar
ban from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
But even before that, Nigeria's national carrier, the Nigeria
Airways has been banned from flying to London since February,
because of alleged frauds in its airplane insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
