<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Down Due to Labor Day Holiday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was lower
late today, with trading quiet due to the Labor Day public holiday
in the country.
</P>
<P>
At close of trading, the Australian dollar was suspended at
72.77 U.S. cents, down from 72.86 U.S. cents locally late Friday.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank foreign exchange senior trader John Wheatley
said it had been a very quiet day for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"The ANZ job ads coming out showing fair growth seemed to spark
a bit of a rally, but it was very short lived and there was very
little volume going through," Wheatley said.
</P>
<P>
The Australia &AMP; New Zealand Banking Corp. Ltd., said the number
of job advertisements rose a seasonally adjusted 2.9 percent in
September from August.
</P>
<P>
"I think the market is just waiting for some fresh news," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The official cash rate currently stands at 5.0 percent,
following five 50-basis points cuts since July last year, with the
last occurring on July 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
Markets have largely factored in a sixth cut by the end of the
year, with most punters betting the Reserve Bank of Australia will
make its move in November.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 88.71 yen at close, little changed
 from 88.74 here Friday, and at 1.2795 marks, down from 1.2828.
</P>
