<HEADLINE> Construction of New Yangtze Bridge Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Work on the second highway
bridge across the Yangtze River in Nanjing started here today.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony this morning, Chen Huanyou, secretary
of the Jiangsu Provincial Committee of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), unveiled a signboard bearing the bridge's name
inscribed by Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Amid pounding of drums and cheers of jubilant crowds, a steel
coffer sank into the Yangtze river, the longest in China.
</P>
<P>
The new bridge, 11 km downstream of the existing Nanjing
Bridge, spans the third largest island in the Yangtze. It is
composed of Nancha and Beicha bridges and a 16-km-long road, and
has a total length of 21.197 km.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is scheduled for completion on July 2001, at a total
cost of 3.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Nancha Bridge is a 2,958-meter-long cable-stayed bridge
with the main span sprawling 628 meters. It is believed to be the
third longest bridge in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Beicha Bridge has a pre-stressed concrete structure with a
length of 2,212 meters. It will have six lanes with a width of 32
meters and be equipped with up-to-date monitoring and lighting
systems.
</P>
<P>
As a hub of transportation on the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze, Nanjing is currently equipped with four national
roads and a trunk line.
</P>
<P>
Operation of the new bridge will alleviate the traffic jams on
existing Nanjing Bridge and promote economic growth not only in
Jiangsu but also in Anhui, Shandong and Zhejiang provinces, a
local government official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fires Scorch 96,700 Hectares of Forest in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Fires had scorched 96,700
hectares of forest in Indonesia by September 30, a senior official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Forestry Djamaloedin Soeryohadikoesoemo told
reporters at the Information Ministry that out of the scorched
forest 70,200 hectares are production forest.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indonesian government has been working hard to
distinguish the forest fires which started in Sumatra and
Kalimantan islands in mid-August.
</P>
<P>
Djamaloedin and several ministers from the Agriculture
Ministry, Public Works Ministry, Communication Ministry and
Environment Ministry introduced government measures taken to cope
with the fires and haze caused by the fires. They said the
situation now is better than last month as rain has come in some
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministers and some experts said the El Nino phenomenon was
the main cause of the forest fires, which have brought heavy
economic losses and severe health effect to people in the country
and neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, President Soeharto apologized again to neighboring
countries affected by haze and smoke caused by Indonesian forest
fires.
</P>
<P>
The country pledged to continue exploring every avenue to fight
the fires, Soeharto said at the ceremony of the Armed Forces 52nd
anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
He ordered armed forces members at all levels to step up
efforts to deal with the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government officially apologized last month to
its Southeast Asian neighbors for the choking haze.
</P>
<P>
Thick smoke from fires raging across 300,000 hectares of forest
has been hanging over Malaysia and Singapore during the past two
months. At one stage the smoke also reached the Philippines and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 30,000 people in Sumatra and Kalimantan, plus
tens of thousands in Malaysia and Singapore, have reportedly been
suffering from respiratory illnesses and eye irritations.
</P>
<P>
"Haze has interrupted sea, land and air transportation. It has
caused price hikes of daily needs in some parts of the country and
food scarcity in remote areas," said Soeharto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
