<HEADLINE> 150 Tamil Rebels Killed, 200 Injured in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 Tamil rebels were
killed and over 200 others injured in a fierce fighting Sunday
with government troops in Northern province of Sri Lanka, military
 spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Ink Dewage said the troops, advancing further north
from their earlier held positions near Puliyankulam, Northern
province, confronted a large group of rebels of the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) near the Mankulam-Mullaitivu Road
about 9 a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The troops met strong resistance from the rebels, who engaged
the troops with mortars. However, supported by artillery and air
fire, the troops were able to defeat the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Ground troops confirmed that over 150 rebels were killed and
more than 200 injured while 34 soldiers were killed and 62 others
wounded in the cross fire. A Mi-24 military helicopter was
slightly injured due to the rebel fire, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting a 14-year-old war for a
separate state in the north and east of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The government troops launched the campaign on the Puliyankulam
town in an effort to capture a highway that links the
government-held Vavuniya to Kilinochchi, which lies further north.
</P>
<P>
This vital supply route to the north of the island has always
been assaulted by the rebels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
