<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man-Made Canal at Three Gorges Put Into Navigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A 3.5-km-long canal, also
known as the "man-made Yangtze River," officially opened for
navigational service this morning at the Three Gorges Dam area on
the middle reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The canal was specially built for construction of a gigantic dam
and generator workshops situated between two parallel cofferdams.
The canal is capable of accommodating ships of 3,000 dwt
(dead weight tonnages).
</P>
<P>
Construction began on May 8, 1993, on the man-made canal, which
was put into operation on May 1 this year. The canal is believed
to outsize the Suez and Panama canals in both width and water
levels.
</P>
<P>
The man-made river course, where the second locking of the
Yangtze will be conducted when construction of the big dam and
generator rooms is completed, will be in service until October
2002. 
</P>
</TEXT>
