<HEADLINE> India to Buy Liquefied Natural Gas from Oman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Oman, one of the major
exporters of liquefied natural gas (LNG), has offered to sell
India up to two million tons of LNG a year, official sources said
here today.
</P>
<P>
A new proposal by Oman to sell LNG to India came up during the
second India-Oman Joint Commission meeting in Dubai and Indian
Minister of State for Commerce B.B. Ramaiah is in Oman leading the
delegation at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We consider LNG as the future oil for India and we will be
depending on LNG in a big way to meet our energy needs," Executive
Director of Indian Oil Corporation A.M. Uplenchwar said.
</P>
<P>
India would use LNG to feed a number of coastal power plants. A
few private sector companies were currently importing LNG on a
limited scale and the import of LNG can be effected only through
big outfits, he said.
</P>
<P>
India would need up to ten million tons of LNG annually to meet
its requirements in the coming years, General Manager of Oil India
Ltd. J.M.B. Baruah said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
