<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy Discusses Passport Issue With Canadian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy has telephoned his Canadian counterpart Lloyd Axworthy
on forged Canadian passports held by two suspected Israeli secret
agents in a failed assassination attempt in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jerusalem Post newspaper today, to two foreign
ministers focused on the question of how forged Canadian
passports ended up in the hands of the two attackers.
</P>
<P>
The suspected agents of the Israeli intelligence service Mossad
disguised themselves as tourists carrying Canadian passports and
attacked Hamas political leader Khalid Mashiel in Jordan on
September 25. The two are now in Jordanian police custody.
</P>
<P>
Declaring the use of its passports by foreign agents to be
unacceptable, the enraged Canadian government recalled its
ambassador to Israel on Friday for consultations and said it was
considering further actions.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry noted that Sunday's conversation took
place in a "good atmosphere" but gave no further details.
Meanwhile, officials of the ministry also held talks with Canadian
diplomats in Tel Aviv in an attempt to straighten out the affair.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Axworthy stressed his country's reputation in the
Middle East remains intact despite the incident, saying that he
had very extensive discussions with a number of Middle East
foreign ministers and clarified Canadian situation so there would
be no misunderstanding in the region about Canadian involvement.
</P>
<P>
Norman Spector, a former Canadian ambassador to Israel and now
president and publisher of the Jerusalem Post newspaper, said that
while the incident poses "a serious issue" for Canadian-Israeli
relations, "ultimately, we'll get over it."
</P>
<P>
However he admitted this "could take some time." he said
Israeli government should "seriously question the use of these
(Canadian) passports, and also the use of passports belonging to
dual citizens, some of whom are working in Jewish organizations,
in order to avoid such incident."
</P>
<P>
Canadian officials would "make it pretty clear (to the
Israelis) that they don't want such incidents to happen again," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
