<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Approves Yassin's Return to Gaza: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel has approved the
return of Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, founder and spiritual leader of
the militant Islamic group Hamas, to Gaza today accompanied by
Jordanian King Hussein, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israeli officials conditioned the return of Yassin on
the release of two Israeli secret agents detained by Jordanian
police in a botched assassination attempt on Hamas leader in
Jordan Khalid Mashiel.
</P>
<P>
Yassin was released to Jordan last week after serving nine
years of a life sentence in Israeli jail, reportedly in exchange
for the exit from Jordan of three Israeli backup agents in the
murder mission.
</P>
<P>
The Hamas founder is expected to fly to Gaza aboard King
Hussein's helicopter via Ramallah, where he is to meet and pick up
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat.
Arafat has visited Yassin in an Amman hospital days ago.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Gaza have decorated the streets and storefronts
in order to award the Hamas founder a hero's welcome. The ceremony
organized by the PNA and Hamas will be held in the Gaza Stadium.
</P>
<P>
The release of Yassin was reportedly part of a secret deal reached
between King Hussein and Israeli government. But the king denied
there was such a deal.
</P>
<P>
The two agents of the Israeli intelligence service Mossad
carrying forged Canadian passports were arrested on September 25
by Jordanian police for attacking Mashiel in front of his
office with an injection of poison. Mashiel was hospitalized for
respiratory problems caused by the toxic and is recovering.
</P>
<P>
The incident has marred relations between Israel and both
Jordan and Canada, which has recalled its ambassador in protest.
</P>
<P>
It also sparked a political uproar cross Israel's political
spectrum as the opposition camp is demanding Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's resignation for his "arrogance, inexperience
and obtuseness" in making the decision to order the Mossad attack
against Mashiel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio quoted Israeli officials as saying
that the two Israelis were expected to return home soon.
Commenting on the Hamas demand for releasing more Hamas
detainees, the officials said that Israel intended only to free
some Palestinian prisoners who were not involved in killing
Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Yassin's release was hailed by Hamas as a major victory by the
militant organization in its relentless fight to destroy Israel
and the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli analysts said that the gala ceremony to be held for
Yassin by Hamas and the PNA indicated the delicate relations
between the two sides, which have been rocky for most of the time.
</P>
<P>
Menahem Klerner, a political scientist of the Bar-Illan
University, said that both Hamas and Arafat are trying to reap the
benefits from Yassin's return. The PNA's decision to welcome
Yassin's return was "part of Arafat's carrot-and-stick doctrine"
in dealing with the Hamas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hamas' continued suicide bombing campaign, the latest being
the attacks in central Jerusalem's two open markets that killed 25
people, has caused extensive damages to the peace process. The
PNA, under increasing Israeli and American pressure, is launching
a crackdown on Hamas activists after failing to woo the
organization into the peace camp.
</P>
<P>
Yassin founded the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) in 1987,
but he was arrested in 1988 in Gaza for ordering terror attacks
against Israel and sentenced into life sentence the year after.
</P>
<P>
His health has been deteriorating in recent years, and now he
is wheel chair-bound after being paralyzed in his arms and legs
and suffering from both breathing and hearing problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
