<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Sufferes Economic Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has suffered economic decline
this year, according to the 1997 report on least developed countries
(LDC) issued by the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
The United States government publication, Washington Line, quoted
the report as saying that other countries undergoing economic
regression are Afghanistan, the Democratic Republic of congo, Guinea,
Haiti, liberia, Madagascar, Malawi, Niger, Principe and Sao Tome,
Sudan and Togo.
</P>
<P>
The economies of these countries are said to have become increasingly
remote with markedly worsend social conditions from the mainstrean
global economy.
</P>
<P>
"These countries are not suffering from a temporary cyclical
economic downturn, but from the degradation of state and social
institutions," says the Washington Line quoting Nakha Sarr, UNCTAD
special coordinator for Africa and LDCs.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD called for an increased focus on how LDC countries can
take advantage of the Uruguay round trade agreement to increase supply
capacity and improve access to developed countries markets.
</P>
<P>
Sarr said the immediate impact of the Uruguay agreement on most
LDCs has been rather negative.
</P>
<P>
Pricing policies, research, technology, extension services,
marketing and other such concerns should be closely addressed by the
LDCs to ensure agriculture, which accounts for over one third of the
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of most of these nations, continues to be
the leading factor in the economy, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Then the LDCs can record faster economic growth," Sarr said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
