<HEADLINE> Lebanese Government Urged to Cut Public Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A top Lebanese banker has urged
the government to take measures to cut down the huge public
deficit by controlling expenditures in public departments.
</P>
<P>
Unless the government takes immediate actions to settle the
deficit, the country's economic, social and monetary stability
would be gravely undermined, warned Francois Bassil, president of
Lebanese Bank Association.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspaper Beirut Times today, Bassil sounded
the alarm at a lecture on Lebanese economic and political future
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said the public deficit, estimatedly accounting for 57
percent of the total expenditure, would take many years to
reduce. "The government must apply severe austerity measures in
all ministries and public departments," he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bassil accused that some domestic companies,
commissioned by the government to implement development projects,
are receiving kickbacks from foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
"These unjustified kickbacks are eventually paid for from the
pockets of the citizens and the government's treasury," he said,
adding that it would also ruin the reputation of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He called on the government to scrutinize all foreign and local
contracting and consulting companies that were vying for a cut in
the multi-billion dollar projects.
</P>
<P>
But he declined to say if some cabinet ministers are involved
in this money scam, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
