<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso, Shares Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso and share
prices fell sharply today due to a tight liquidity supply, higher
interest rates and rumors of more local companies defaulting on
bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The peso weakened to 34.926 pesos to one U.S. dollar at the
local dealing system, from last Friday's record low of 34.494
pesos. Since early July, the currency has been devaluated by 31.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate between the peso and the greenback quickly
fell to 34.926 peso per dollar and remained static through
mid-afternoon in extremely light trading.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts said the central bank's move to raise the
overnight borrowing rate from 12 percent to 14 percent, a plan to
impose a one percent volatility limit, and more firms' application
for delaying the payment of their loans marred the investors'
confidence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the local bourses plunged as a result of the
currency concerns and soaring interest rates. Interbank overnight
lending rate in the country rose to 105 percent from last Friday's
90 percent.
</P>
<P>
The 30-share composite index tumbled 68.43 points, or 3.4
percent, to 1,961.24, breaking the psychological 2,000-point
level.
</P>
<P>
To curb the free fall of the peso and the plunge of the shares,
the Bankers Association of the Philippines is holding a meeting to
decide whether to impose the one-percent volatility limit.
</P>
<P>
The move means if the dollar gains more than one percent
against the peso, trading on the currency exchange will be halted
temporarily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
