<HEADLINE> US to Apply More Pressure on Israel: Lebanese FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares
Boueiz has said that he believed Washington will have to apply
more pressure on Israel for it to make peace with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper The Daily Star reported today that Boueiz made
the remark Sunday night upon returning from Now York where he
attended the 52nd annual session of the United Nations General
Assembly and held talks with a number of his Arab counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz said the United States had given Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu a year of freedom to choose his own path
toward peace, which came out to have plunged the peace process
into an abyss.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in Mideast peacemaking began last March when
Netanyahu decided to build a housing project for 30,000 Jewish
settlers in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as their
future capital.
</P>
<P>
The "peace process ball is now in the American court," Boueiz
said, adding the question now faced was how the defiant Israeli
position would be reconciled with American position.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz thought U.S. policy in the Middle East under Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright as being aimed at reactivating all
tracks in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"However, Netanyahu's present position is a threat to this new
trend," he added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that judging from Netanyahu's latest
declaration to continue with the settlements, it is apparent that
Israeli government's policy is not receptive to the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
