<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, October 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A bomb scare in a Tel Aviv bus over Sunday night
proved to be a false alarm, Israel Radio quoted police as saying
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio interrupted its normal broadcast Sunday night to
report that a bomb had exploded on the No. 5 bus in northern Tel
Aviv. Police spokeswoman Linda Munuhin said the bomb was suspected
to be planted by an Arab, who aroused the attention of the driver
and fled after the driver began questioning his identity.
(Israel-Bomb Scare)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Urban population in China rose to 515.11 million by
the end of last year, about 43 percent of its total population,
according to the latest statistics of the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Of China's 666 cities, 11 have a population of more than two
million each. Next come 23 with a population of one to two
million, 44 with 500,000 to a million people, 159 with 200,000 to
500,000 people, and 393 cities with less than 200,000.
(China-Urban Population-Increase)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Serbia and Montenegro, the two republics of
Yugoslavia, held presidential elections Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The election in the republic of Serbia was the second round, in
which 7.21 million registered voters will cast votes at polling
stations in 29 constituencies. In the first round election held on
September 21, none of the 17 candidates got the required 50
percent of the votes although the turnout was more than 50 percent
that validated the election result. (Yugoslavia-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai ruling parties have agreed that the planned
cabinet reshuffle will take place after October 15, press reports
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached Sunday night after three hours of
consultation between all the senior figures of the coalition
parties including Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, said the
report. (Thailand-Reshuffle)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Momcilo Krajisnik, Serb member of the Presidency of
the Republic of Bosnia, made two proposals to ease the tension
caused by the NATO-led Stabilization Force's (SFOR) seizure of
four Serb TV transmitters, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik suggested that the SFOR withdraw from the stations to
ensure a normal situation and press freedom in the Republic of
Srpska. He also proposed that the TV transmitters be technically
linked together so that another two Serb radio and TV stations --
Banjaluka and Pale -- could simultaneously broadcast programs.
(Bosnia-SFOR) 
</P>
