<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Alliance Claims Major Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan anti-Taliban forces
have claimed that they had made further gains around the northern
Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces have confirmed the loss of several important
areas around Mazar-e-sharif. The fighting now is raging close to
Hairatan port in east of Mazar-e-Sharif, the only major sector
controlled by the Taliban, reports reaching here today from Kabul
said.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that heavy battle was going on around Hairatan
port with both sides using rockets, heavy artillery and other
weapons for the control of the strategic area which links
Afghanistan to neighboring Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of anti-Taliban alliance fighters were seen in action
 Sunday in their bid to recapture Hairatan port and plug all
possibilities for Taliban's future advance towards Mazar-e-Sharif,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Taliban officials conceded Sunday that their troops had
retreated from Mazar-e-Sharif Airport but denied the reports they
had been routed from all the major areas both to the west and east
of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
"We have pulled out of the airport voluntarily but our troops
are within the outskirts of Mazar-e-Sharif," one Taliban
representative was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, one report quoted spokesman for the anti-Taliban
alliance named Dr. Talib as claiming that they have controlled the
areas both to the east and west of the northern city.
</P>
<P>
He said that their troops had recaptured all important areas
from the Taliban and the fighting was now intensifying around the
Hairatan junction and the port as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
