<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Needs 38.5 Million Dollars Annually for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambia needs 50 billion Kwacha
(38.5 million U.S. Dollars) every year to rehabilitate and
reconstruct the country's dilapidated road network, Zambia Daily
Mail reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Kelly Walubita, Minister of Communications
and Transport, as saying in a recently released publication
titled Road Sector Investment Program that
the roads in the country were in the last part of their design
life.
</P>
<P>
The program is a 10-year plan for soliciting donor funds to
supplement local resources. Under the 10-year investment program
which has been launched starting with Lusaka roads, Zambia will
offer regular maintenance to roads.
</P>
<P>
The initial five years of the repair exercise requires about
385 million Dollars, part of which will be raised from road users
through various ways including fuel levy.
</P>
<P>
Walubita attributed the deteriorating state to lack of funding
and proper management of the road network which has made the
routine and periodic road maintenance be neglected.
</P>
<P>
Most of the roads in Zambia have not been attended to for over
30 years despite the fact that every road needs to be resealed
every five years. The current poor state of the roads has been
caused to a great extent by lack of regular maintenance.
</P>
<P>
At present, local resources have fallen short of meeting the
required funds to cater for the backlog of deferred maintenance
and the desired levels of road rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the World Bank has given Zambia a loan of
about 91 billion Kwacha (70 million U.S. Dollars) to finance the
initial road repairs in the capital as part of the country-wide
exercise under the Roadsip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
