<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Protect Interest of Retrenchees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambian workers to
be retrenched will get their packages on time as the government
has taken measures to reduce the sufferings of the affected
people, Finance Minister Ronalt Penza has said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said in Livingstone, southern Zambia on Sunday
that the government has changed the culture of throwing people on
streets, according to "Zambia Daily Mail" today.
</P>
<P>
"Retrenched workers will have to get their packages within a
short time after being laid off to reduce sufferings people have
been going through. The government has realized that and changed
the approach and that is why we are here planning for the
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Penza, who is in Livingstone to have opened the permanent
secretaries workshop on planning and budgeting, also referred to
many other issues including merging of ministries.
</P>
<P>
Asked about which ministries in particular are under his focus
for consideration to merge, he mentioned ministries of education,
science and technology, ministries of community development and
social welfare and youth and sport.
</P>
<P>
He said a better way forward has to be mooted to cut down on
wide resources allocation to target priorities in these ministries.
</P>
<P>
"If we ourselves shy away from biting the bullet in terms of
far reaching structural reforms to make the public sector more
responsive to the needs of the nation in the new millennium, we
cannot justify continuing to tell the private sector to
restructure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Penza said hard decisions must focus on reducing low priority
expenditures and it must involve merging ministries to avoid
duplication and unnecessary costs, reducing the cost of foreign
missions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
