<HEADLINE> Kenya Attracts $21 Million Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi Stock Exchange
(NSE) has attracted net foreign investment of 21.4 million U.S.
Dollars since the beginning of this year, The East African
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly paper said that the equities market in Nairobi had
maintained foreign investor participation although the debt
market had suffered from panic selling following the stand-off
between the Kenyan government and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF).
</P>
<P>
In the past two months, foreign investors have re-discounted
bonds worth 72 million Dollars with a net capital inflow standing
at 2.3 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Portfolio Investments (FPI) accounted for 37.6
percent of the total market turnover in two months of July and
August.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that even in July, when the impact of the
IMF-Kenya stand-off was greatest, FPIs accounted for 39.8 percent
of the monthly turnover.
</P>
<P>
The FPIs have propelled the NSE turnover to record levels this
year, said the paper, adding that the turnover had hit 78.2
million Dollars mark last month and should easily surpass the 94
million Dollars mark by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, total market turnover recorded 61.2 million Dollars
which was itself an 18 percent increase over the 1995 level.
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out that as one of the leading stock
exchanges in Africa, Kenya must have benefited from the pool of
investment funds set aside for African markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
