<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB South Africa's Number One Killer: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Tuberculosis (TB) is South
Africa's number one killer, a survey has found.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, TB killed more South Africans that AIDS, malaria,
measles and murder combined, an annual report of South Africa
Survey said.
</P>
<P>
More than 158,000 people had TB, some 27 percent of whom were
also HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
The Western Cape Province had the highest TB rate, about 1.5
times higher than the national average. However, only 12 percent
of the TB sufferers in that province were HIV-positive, compared
with 45 percent in Kwazulu-Natal, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that TB has mounted a comeback worldwide.
Although TB is usually curable, it led to deaths owing to poor
health care conditions and lack of financial means in third world
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
