<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Sanctions 1.33B Dollars for Fisheries Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
sanctioned 5.86 billion taka (about 1.33 billion U.S. dollars) for
the country's fisheries sector during the Fifth Five-year Plan
period (1997-98 to 2001-2002), said sources from the Department of
Fisheries today.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, both the production and export earnings from
the sector will be brought at sustainable levels, generating a
huge number of employment opportunities, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
Assisted by the government and different donor agencies such as
the Asian Development Bank and the World Bank, they added, the
fund will be spent in providing financial and technical support to
improve the productivity as well as to develop the quality of
shrimps and fish.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the plan is to motivate and integrate the
country's fishermen and prospective fish farmers in the production
activities, the sources said. With this in view, the fisheries
management and research will be expanded and training activities
be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
The country's fish production has been projected at around 2
million tons by the end of the five-year plan from the current
1.373 million tons, the sources stated.
</P>
<P>
The country's marine fish production has been projected at 0.4
million tons against the present 0.294 million tons, they said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, export earrings from sector has been fixed
at 23 billion taka (about 521 million dollars) against the current
export earnings of around 16 billion taka (about 364 million
dollars), the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Necessary measures would be taken to ensure the quality of fish
for marketing both in the local and international markets, the
sources said. Necessary steps will also be taken to contain
contamination of the water bodies by industrial wastes and
minimize the use of pesticides and fertilizers with a view to
saving the country's fish resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
