<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City's Ports of Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- More than half the people and
nearly 80 percent of the vehicles entering or exiting China pass
through the ports of entry in the Shenzhen Special Economic Zone
in Guangdong Province, next to Hongkong.
</P>
<P>
Before the special economic zone was founded in 1980, there
were only two small ports of entry, but the city now has 12 land,
air, and sea outlets used by both local and overseas passengers
and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The border crossing at Luohu and the cargo outlet at Huanggang
are the largest in China, and Yantian Port has become one of the
ten largest sea ports, while Shenzhen Airport is the country's
fourth largest.
</P>
<P>
In the past 17 years, China's central government and the
Guangdong provincial and Shenzhen city governments have spent over
two billion yuan (240 million US dollars) on these outlets along
the province's 260-kilometer coastline and the 27.5-km border with
Hongkong.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were 63.21 million people going in or out of the
country through Shenzhen, accounting for 53.3 percent of the
country's total. The number of vehicles was 8.53 million, or 77.6
percent of the total, and foreign trade amounted to 43.14 million
tons, or 10.7 percent of the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, Uzbekistan Sign Two Economic Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and Uzbekistan
today signed two agreements to expand and deepen their long-term
trade, economic and industrial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreements -- a trade agreement and an investment guarantee
agreement, were signed by Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Anwar
Ibrahim and his Uzbek counterpart Victor Chjen who is here on a
three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The two governments agreed to provide the necessary assistance
and encourage private enterprises and organizations to explore
opportunities in trade and investment, a statement by the
Malaysian Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) said
today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's total trade with Uzbekistan stood at 20.3 million
ringgit (about 8.12 million U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian export items were footwear, commodities, rubber
tires and tubes, office machines and computers, apparel and
clothing and electrical machinery appliances and parts.
</P>
<P>
Export opportunities for Malaysian companies to Uzbekistan
include electronic components and parts, automotive and parts,
furniture and office equipment, MITI said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's imports from Uzbekistan comprised mainly textiles,
fibers (silk and cotton) and general industrial machinery (heating
and cooling equipment).
</P>
<P>
Malaysian investment in Uzbekistan has so far amounted to 248.8
million ringgit (nearly 100 million U.S. dollars) in sectors such
as hotel refurbishment, oil and gas exploration,
telecommunications, manufacturing of plastic products, trading,
tourism and ticketing, property, hotel and gaming, according to
MITI.
</P>
<P>
Business and investment opportunities in Uzbekistan for
Malaysian private sector include mineral resources, processing of
agricultural products, transport and communications, textiles and
consumer products and construction and property development, MITI
said.
</P>
<P>
The Uzbek deputy prime minister arrived here Sunday on a
three-day official visit to Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
