<HEADLINE> Special Permits For Private Enterprises In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Jian'ou, a small underdeveloped
city in China's Fujian province has begun issuing special permits
for private enterprises and individually-owned firms, in an effort
to speed up local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The government of Jian'ou in the northern part of Fujian has
issued a number of documents like a 'credibility
certificate', 'production priority certificate', 'transport check
exemption certificate', and 'certificate for the protection of
major private enterprises' to recognize and protect some of its
major private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The decision to use the certificates came after Chen Yonghao, a
nationally-acclaimed private entrepreneur, was extorted by local
officials. In trying to persuade Chen to stay in Jian'ou, the city
government vowed to take steps to better protect private
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To date, 25 enterprises have received the credibility
certificate', which gives them special support from local
financial institutions. And twenty-two firms were given
the 'production priority card', and 21 were given exemptions from
transport checks.
</P>
<P>
There are also 23 businesses enjoying special protection from
any unauthorized visits by organizations or individuals as well as
special protection from the local public security
authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
