<HEADLINE> Inflation Remains at Low Level in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' inflation rate
in September moved up to 5.3 percent from August's 4.5 percent,
according to statistics released by the National Statistic Office
(NSC) today.
</P>
<P>
Measured on a year-on-year base, the inflation rate in the
country still averaged below five percent, much lower than last
year's average of 8.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NSC attributed the slight increase in September's inflation
to the hike of food prices. The inflation rate for food alone rose
to two percent from 0.6 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
In Metro Manila, the inflation rate rose to 6.8 percent from
5.8 percent while other regions also registered higher inflation
rates than last month.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the government's statistics did not
reflect the real changes in the consumer prices, citing that the
sharp fall of the peso in the regional currency woes has pushed up
the prices of basic commodities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government said the lower inflation and the strong
performance of exports meant that the country's economic
fundamentals are still very sound despite the current currency
turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
