<HEADLINE> Chinese Peasant Becomes "Edison" Of East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Cao Jiangang, a former peasant in
Ningbo, a city on the east coast of China, has been honored as the
"Edison of Ningbo" by American experts for his 1,800 inventions.
</P>
<P>
Cao attended a seminar on dynamic engineering in early 1997 and
surprised 50 professors and senior engineers with his research
report. Although he is only an assistant engineer, he has solved a
lot of difficult problems that have puzzled academics for years.
</P>
<P>
Cao, 37, started farming when he graduated from junior middle
school in 1975. But, in 1982, when China's reforms were still in
their initial stage, he set up an instrument and meter plant with
6,000 yuan in savings, an enormous amount at that time. By the
1990s, he had set up a high-tech corporation in Ningbo, a port
city in Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, Cao has developed 1,800 kinds of new
products, many of which are in extensive use in high-tech
industries.
</P>
<P>
One of them, an instrument for blood analysis, proved to be
more efficient than computer-controlled equipment imported from
the US, and was praised by an American businessman who invited Cao
to the US and was ready to give him 100,000 US dollars for moving
to the US. Cao declined the offer.
</P>
<P>
Cao's inventions have been applied to various areas and some
are ordered by many major Chinese enterprises like Baoshan Iron
and Steel Complex, Yanshan Petrochemical Corp. and the Daqing
Oilfield. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
