<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 07:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tel Aviv Bomb Scare Proves False Alarm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A bomb scare in a Tel Aviv bus
overnight proved to be a false alarm, Israel Radio quoted police
as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio interrupted its normal broadcast Sunday night to
report that a bomb had exploded on the No. 5 bus in northern Tel
Aviv. Police spokeswoman Linda Munuhin said the bomb was suspected
to be planted by an Arab, who aroused the attention of the driver
and fled after the driver began questioning his identity.
</P>
<P>
The driver reportedly heard an explosion after passengers were
evacuated from the bus. But Tel Aviv police, who rushed to the
scene of the "attack," found no trace of either a bomb or a
terrorist.
</P>
<P>
"There was no attack. There was no bomb," said another police
spokeswoman Nitza Friedman. "The driver said a fellow with a 'dark
complexion' had aroused his suspicion and when questioned the
passenger quickly left the bus."
</P>
<P>
On the driver's account of an explosion from the trash bin of
the bus, police determined that he might have stepped on a paper
bag and mistook the cracking sound as an explosion.
</P>
<P>
The bomb scare showed the increasing fear among Israeli public
of more terror attacks following the recent wave of suicide
bombings in Jerusalem's two open markets, in which 25 people were
killed and over 300 wounded.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security forces have been on high alert and beefed up
security in public places. In the past, crowded buses used to be
the main targets of Islamic suicide attackers who intended to
cause as many casualties as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
