<HEADLINE> Philippines' Exports Continue to Expand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' merchandise
export revenue in the first eight months of this year posed a 22.8
percent increase compared with the corresponding period of 1996,
the National Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
"Revenue earned from merchandise exports posted a 22.8 percent
increase as January to August 1997 receipts reached 16.023 billion
U.S. dollars, exceeding the 13.050 billion dollars in 1996 by
2.973 billion dollars," said the office in a statement issued
here.
</P>
<P>
The office said that value of exports for August alone grew
27.2 percent to 2.256 billion dollars, an increase of 482 million
dollars from the 1.774 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"Compared with the previous month, exports gained 9.1 percent
(in August) from 2.067 billion dollars," it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that August's exports revenue from electronics and
components, accounting for 43.9 percent of the total, rose 48.5
percent to 989.45 million dollars from 666.49 million dollars a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
The depreciation of the Philippine peso and the recent recovery
of the world electronics market could be attributed to the fast
export expansion in the country, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Since July 11, the peso fell over 30 percent against the
dollar. The de facto devaluation of the currency made the
country's export products more competitive on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan, Singapore and the Netherlands remain
the country's major trade partners.  
</P>
</TEXT>
