<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee and Tea Export Prices Fluctuate in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Coffee and tea prices
increased slightly in the world market while those for cotton
dropped because of the dry weather pattern, said the latest issue
of the monthly Economic Review Report of the Bank of Tanzania
(BOT).
</P>
<P>
While prices for robusta remained unchanged compared with
July's figures of 1.7 US Dollars per kilogram, prices for other
types of coffee including arabica witnessed an upward trend reaching
4.3 US Dollars per kilogram compared with 4.1 US Dollars per
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Tea prices increased to an average of about two US Dollars
from 1.9 US Dollars per kilogram as was reported in July.
</P>
<P>
The BOT report attributed the increase in coffee prices to the
fear that the dry weather pattern could harm the world coffee
crop. As for the tea prices, it attributed the increase to floods
in Bangladesh, which threatened the short term supplies of the
crop, that setting of the price surge.
</P>
<P>
Cotton prices dropped slightly to an average of 1.7 US Dollars
per kilogram from 1.8 US Dollars recorded in July while sisal
prices remained relatively stable at around 770 US Dollars per
ton, the BOT monthly report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
