<HEADLINE> World Habitat Day Observed in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- On the occasion of the World
Habitat Day, Bangladeshi President Justice Shahabuddin Ahmed and
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina today called for efforts to build the
country's cities into better ones.
</P>
<P>
A huge population of Bangladesh reside in the cities, and so
they should be turned into modern and healthy ones, the president
said in his message carried in the local newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
He added that proper and timely planning and its implementation
are necessary to this effect.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the country would get directions
from city planners, architects, engineers and researchers.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister in her message called for non-government
initiatives to supplement the government efforts to implement
people-oriented programs for improving the standards of the cities
in the country.
</P>
<P>
She said to keep pace with the rapid urbanization in
Bangladesh, steps are being taken to provide pure drinking water
supply, sewerage systems, educational institutions, play grounds,
parks, gardens, health care, social and physical infrastructure
facilities in all cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said she was hopeful that the non-government
initiators would come forward and work side by side with her
government to help implement the programs to improve the
conditions of the cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Today, local English newspapers also published essays or
articles to mark the World Habitat Day.  
</P>
