<HEADLINE> India Takes Measures to Enhance Air Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- India's Civil Aviation
Ministry has decided to enhance air safety by bringing the entire
space of the country under the cover of secondary surveillance
radars (SSR) and satellite-based systems by the end next year, a
government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Airports Authority of India (AAI) has been asked to speed
up work on SSR installation projects. It has been decided to keep
a close watch on the Mumbai (Bombay) and New Delhi SSR projects
where installation of Raytheon radars have been plagued.
</P>
<P>
The government has already made air collision avoidance
system/traffic collision avoidance system mandatory for all
aircraft operating in Indian airspace. 
</P>
