<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Auto Parts Makers Urged to Produce Accessories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Board
of Investment (BOI) of Thailand has urged Thai auto parts makers
to expand their production from original equipment to general
accessories to weather the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Making accessories will widen their markets, as sales of
original equipment are limited to orders from major assemblers,
said Chakramon Phasukvanich, deputy secretary-general of BOI.
</P>
<P>
Because of the economic slump, car assemblers in the country
have reduced production by as much as 50 percent and Nissan has
temporarily suspended its production of pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has about 200 companies making original equipment for
major car brands. Some parts makers have cut production to half or
one-third of capacity.
</P>
<P>
Auto parts makers in Thailand are protected by the requirement
for local assemblers to use their products and therefore have made
no improvements in quality in the past two years, Chakramon was
quoted today by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
If exports cannot be increased, several parts makers are at
risk of closure before the end of the year, Chakramon said.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not believe that the present economic slowdown
would affect Thailand's goal of becoming the hub of the automobile
industry in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
In the first eight months of this year, exports of Thai-made
automobile products, including assembled cars, engines, parts,
motorcycles and kits, were up 145.8 percent from the same period
of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
