<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Ernesto Samper summoned a meeting of military commanders for
Monday after 28 policemen, soldiers and judicial officials were
killed over the weekend in attacks by rebels and gunmen.
</P>
<P>
The 28 people were killed in two ambushes in eastern Meta
province in 24 hours, but efforts have so far failed to find who
were responsible for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
A statement of the president's office did not say what measures
military commanders would discuss at the meeting but ruled out the
possibility of declaring a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the president has given precise orders to
his defense minister and the director of the national police to
take all measures necessary to pursue and capture the attackers.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the paramilitary force would be held
responsible for the first attack in which 11 judicial officials,
soldiers and policemen died Friday near the town of San Carlos de
Guaroa. But Carlos Castano, leader of Colombia's largest
paramilitary force, denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
In the second attack, 200 members of the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia (FARC) blew up two police trucks and fired
machine guns and grenades near the town of San Juan de Arama
Saturday, killing 17 policemen. 
</P>
