<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Reshuffle to Take Place After October 15 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Thai ruling parties have agreed
that the planned cabinet reshuffle will take place after October
15, press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached Sunday night after three hours of
consultation between all the senior figures of the coalition
parties including Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
During the consultation, Chavalit asked key members of the six
coalition parties to give breathing space for his government to
address economic problems, especially the plan to rehabilitate 58
suspended finance companies. The rehabilitation plan is scheduled
to be announced on October 15.
</P>
<P>
According to an informed source, Chavalit regarded the
rehabilitation plan as his top priority and has wanted it to be
addressed before the cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Korn Dabbaransi, Chart Pattana party's deputy leader, was
quoted as saying that his party had agreed to the prime minister's
request not to press for a cabinet reshuffle until the 15th of
this month when International Monetary Fund (IMF) officials will
evaluate how well Thailand has abided by its measures.
</P>
<P>
A source said that the evaluation was necessary to determine if
the second and third installments of the IMF-sponsored aid package
would be extended to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has secured 172 billion U.S. dollars in standby credit
from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Chart Pattana has pressed Chavalit for a large-scale reshuffle
and insisted that this has to be done immediately otherwise the
government cannot win public confidence essential for solving the
economic crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
