<HEADLINE> Serbia, Montenegro Hold Presidential Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Serbia and Montenegro, the two
republics of Yugoslavia, held presidential elections today.
</P>
<P>
Today's election in the republic of Serbia was the second
round, in which 7.21 million registered voters will cast votes at
polling stations in 29 constituencies.
</P>
<P>
In the first round election held on September 21, none of the
17 candidates got the required 50 percent of the votes although
the turnout was more than 50 percent that validated the election
result.
</P>
<P>
Zoran Lilich of the election alliance of the leftist parties
and Vojislav Seselj of the Serbian Radical Party, who won maximum
votes in the first round, are contesting the presidency in the
second round.
</P>
<P>
The republic of Montenegro held its first round election today
to choose its president from eight candidates.
</P>
<P>
Two men nominated by the two factions within the ruling
Socialist Democratic Party of Montenegro, namely, the incumbent
President Momir Bulatovich and Prime Minister Milo Djukanovich,
were deemed most hopeful.
</P>
<P>
More than half of the 460,000 registered voters in Montenegro
reportedly went to the polls.
</P>
<P>
So far, no initial results have been made public. 
</P>
