<HEADLINE> Travel Fad in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Increasing numbers of people in
Beijing are going on outings on the weekend or holidays, according
to the Municipal Tourism Bureau, which says that per family travel
expenditures in the Chinese capital were 81.95 yuan (about 10 US
dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
One recent Saturday morning, a man named Wang, and his wife and
son, got on the No.1 Special Tourism Bus at Qianmen in downtown
Beijing headed for the Great Wall at Badaling, 100 kilometers
north of the city.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, we only joined tours organized by our work
unit. But now there are special tourist buses so we can go on our
own." In 1996, Beijing had 76.83 million Chinese tourists, 25.42
million of whom were from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
To meet the growing needs of this business, in early 1996 the
municipal transportation authorities opened 18 special bus routes
to 68 major tourist attractions on the outskirts of the city to
provide more convenient service for people in Beijing and from
other parts of the country and the world.
</P>
<P>
The number of people traveling to remote counties and districts
like Yanqing, Miyun, Changping, Mentougou, and Fangshan have risen
this year, with hotel occupancy rates in these areas now
approaching 100 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
