<HEADLINE> North China Leader In Foreign Investment Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
province used 950 million US dollars in the first half of the
year, a 37 percent increase over a year ago, and making it one of
north country's leaders in the use of overseas investment
</P>
<P>
This fairly recent development is a reversal of the previous
situation in coastal areas. Last year, it had 3.52 billion US
dollars worth of contractual investment, an increase that ranked
first among coastal provinces and municipalities. In 1991 however,
it was at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
Locals attribute this to an improved investment environment. In
the past five years, Hebei spent more than 15 billion yuan
building 6,682 km of new highways.
</P>
<P>
Two expressways, one to Beijing and another to Taiyuan, the
capital of Shanxi Province, and an airport were opened to
traffic. The province had a long history of sea access but no
harbors. Last year, it put seven berths into operation at Jingtang
harbor.
</P>
<P>
As a result, multinationals have begun to look to the
province. Germany's Siemens invested 550 million US dollars in
China's largest joint-ventured power plant, the Hanfeng Power
Plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
