<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Communists to Offer Government New Economic Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy's leftist leader Fausto
Bertinotti said today that he would urge the government to adopt a
new economic program when he meets Prime Minister Romano Prodi
Monday for talks over the government's much debated 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
"We will propose the introduction of a discriminating,
progressive program which would mark a change of direction
compared to the budget bill presented by the government," the
leader of the Communist Refoundation Party told the ANSA news
agency.
</P>
<P>
The government had said that a deficit-slashing 1998 budget is
crucial to Italy's chances of participating in the European
Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) at its very launch in 1999.
</P>
<P>
But Bertinotti said that his party perceives a just Europe as
one that was compatible with "a free and improved health service
and the defense of pensions."
</P>
<P>
The dispute could lead to the fall of the government, as
Prodi's Olive Tree coalition would lose its majority without the
support of Refoundation deputies in the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, Prodi has refused to withdraw the bill and on several
occasions said that if the present governing majority collapses,
he would not try to form a new one. He is due to address
parliament Tuesday on the state of his majority.
</P>
<P>
Bertinotti said that his party would offer a one-year pact to
help fix the terms of the budget and outline a general economic
policy.
</P>
<P>
He said such a pact was needed in order to restore stability to
Italian politics and to avoid further disruption and disagreement.
</P>
<P>
He rejected government MPs' accusation that the communists want
to trip the country up just before it reaches the EMU finishing
line by taking harsh belt-tightening measures.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Monday meeting, Bertinotti said the chances of
an agreement being made is slim. "To reach this accord, the
government must abandon the grotesque claim that Refoundation
wants to undo all the progress that has been made so far this
year," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
