<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebels Deny Links With Missing Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Tamil rebels have
denied any connection with the disappearance of a shipload of
mortar bombs belonging to the Sri Lankan Army, according to
reports monitored here today.
</P>
<P>
The shipload of mortar bombs, which was purchased by the Sri
Lanka Army from Zimbabwe, went missing while it was en route from
Madagascar to Sri Lanka in July.
</P>
<P>
Accusations have been leveled against the Tamil rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), saying that they had
intercepted the shipment during its transport.
</P>
<P>
In a special release from its London headquarters, the LTTE
stated that these accusations were "without foundation."
</P>
<P>
"The episode has also been exploited to tarnish the
international image of the LTTE, in particular to associate the
LTTE with acts of international piracy," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 32,400 rounds of 81-mm mortar bombs were loaded on
the missing ship named Stillus Limmassul.  
</P>
