<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines in Thailand to Follow Thai Airways' Fare Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign airlines operating in
Thailand are expected to increase their air fares soon after the
Thai Airways International(THAI) increased its fares for most
international routes by 3 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Airline operators say that they are now absorbing cost increase
of 40 percent arising from the depreciation of the baht, adding
that a 3 to 5 percent price rise would be nothing compared to the
baht's depreciation.
</P>
<P>
Since October 1, THAI has increased its fares by 5 percent for
first and business class tickets on flights serving the United
States and for all classes on Japanese routes. fares of all
classes to and from Australia, New Zealand and Europe have risen
by 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, however, airlines managers are concerned
that the new prices will cause a further drop in demand, as
outbound travel already decreased because the Thai people have
less money to spend.
</P>
<P>
Travel agents predict that costs of package tours will also
increase because of higher air fares.
</P>
<P>
Under the Thai government's policy of buying Thai and touring
Thailand, outbound travelers have decreased considerably and, as a
result, many small travel agents have closed down.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, airport tax is expected to double, from 250 baht to
500 baht (6.85 U.S. dollars to 13.7 dollars), early next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
