<HEADLINE> SFOR Troops Urged to Leave Serb TV Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Momcilo Krajisnik, Serb member
of the Presidency of the Republic of Bosnia, made two proposals to
ease the tension caused by the NATO-led Stabilization Force's
(SFOR) seizure of four Serb TV transmitters.
</P>
<P>
The proposals were raised when Krajisnik met in Pale, Bosnia,
with Robert Gelbard, a special envoy of U.S. President Bill
Clinton, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported today.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik suggested that the SFOR withdraw from the stations to
ensure a normal situation and press freedom in the Republic of
Srpska.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed that the TV transmitters be technically linked
together so that another two Serb radio and TV stations --
Banjaluka and Pale -- could simultaneously broadcast programs.
</P>
<P>
The Serb official voiced his support for the strike started by
Srpska radio and TV workers.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred SFOR troops occupied the four TV transmitters
in the Republic of Srpska last week in an effort to silence
propaganda hostile to the Dayton treaty signed in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
The SFOR's action was believed to be another signal of NATO's
get-tough policy on Serb factions who did not comply with the
treaty. 
</P>
