<HEADLINE> Atlantis Rescheduled to Land on Earth Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. space shuttle Atlantis
was rescheduled to land on Monday after a delay because of strong
wind and thick clouds, the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA) said.
</P>
<P>
The rearranged landing of the shuttle was for 5:55 p.m. EDT
(2155 GMT) Monday. It was originally scheduled to land at the
Kennedy Space Center in Florida at 6:59 p.m. EDT (2259 GMT) Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Atlantis had two opportunities for landing at the Kennedy Space
Center today, but concerns about clouds and brisk breezes prompted
flight director Linda Ham at the Johnson Space Center's Mission
Control to pass up both opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle is returning after a six-day visit to the Russian
Mir space station to restock and service the ailing station.
</P>
<P>
The shuttle is coming back with astronauts including
Michael Foale, who has been in space for 144 days and stayed in
the Mir for four and a half months.
</P>
<P>
He had been replaced by another American astronaut David Wolf
to stay in the Mir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
