<HEADLINE> China Wins Men's 5,000m Relay in Speed Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China posed a big surprise to win
the men's 5,000m relay Sunday, while South Korea went on to
dominate the Desjardins International short-track speed-skating
competition in Montreal, Canada.
</P>
<P>
After three days of World Cup competition, South Korea led the
medals table with five golds from 10 events, with 14 medals
overall.
</P>
<P>
South Korea rounded off a fabulous meet in the 3,000 meters, as
Dong-sung Kim led a sweep of the men's medals with a time of
5:12.18.
</P>
<P>
South Koreans Yun-mi Kim (5:35.53) and Sang-mi An (5:36.58)
finished one-two in the women's 3,000m final.
</P>
<P>
Saturo Terao picked up Japan's only gold of the meet with his
victory in 1: 31.44 in the men's 1,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Jun-hwan Lee of South Korea was second at 1:31.63 with local
favourite and current world record holder Mark Gagnon winning
bronze for Canada in 1:31.65.
</P>
<P>
The upset of the day came in the men's 5,000m relay, in which
the Chinese team took an early lead and raced to victory in
7:05.43.
</P>
<P>
Canada were second in 7:06.48 and Japan picked up bronze in
7:11.16.
</P>
<P>
"They flat out beat us," said Canadian Derrick Campbell. "It
was a surprise for us they did this well. We didn't skate
terrible by any means."
</P>
<P>
Campbell said China now joins Canada, Japan, reigning world
champions South Korea and reigning Olympic champions Italy -- as a
serious contenders for gold at the 1998 Nagano Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
