<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Autumn Harvest Almost Assured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 6 (Xinhua) -- China's autumn grain crops are
growing better than predicted during the summer drought, "China
Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The first frost, an influential factor after summer drought,
came at a normal time (after September 20). It did not do great
harm to grain crops, the paper quoted Zhao Hanjie, chief of the
Agricultural information Division under the Ministry of
Agriculture as saying.
</P>
<P>
By now, a good grain harvest for this autumn is almost
assured. And until then, field management, including stepped-up
irrigation of dry farms, will further help secure better crops,
Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Since official figures will not be available until after the
harvest, he declined to say whether the expected output is higher
or lower than that of last year.
</P>
<P>
Since July, vast areas of north China and the middle and lower
reaches of the Yangtze River have been hit by drought.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, 9.3 million ha of crops were still
suffering from drought, among which nearly half were said to be
seriously threatened, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Autumn grain production generally accounts for about three
fourths of the country's annual output, and the rest comes from
the summer harvest.
</P>
<P>
This year, a good summer harvest was reported in July with a
record output of nearly 124 million tons of grain, up 10.7 million
tons from that of last summer, and other official statistics
earlier this month showed an increase of nearly two million tons
of early rice.
</P>
<P>
"In all this year's total grain production is favourable," Zhao
said, adding, there will be an increased output of rice in the
south but a decreased output of maize in the north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
