<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Rural Economy Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The rural economy in northeast
China's Liaoning province has emerged as one of the most important
means of economic growth, with industrial output of township
enterprises accounting for 40 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the province's rural output value has
increased four-fold and farmers' net income averaged 2,150 yuan
(259 US dollars) in 1996, 2.4 times that of 1991. In the process
one million farmers have said good-bye to poverty.
</P>
<P>
As China's largest industrial base, Liaoning has gradually
overcome a shortage of agricultural products. Its grain output
totaled 16.6 million tons in 1996, 8.4 percent more than 1991.
</P>
<P>
Total output of vegetables, fruits, meat, egg, and fish in 1996
was above 20 million tons, twice the figure for 1992. A great
quantity of non-staple food is transported to Jilin and
Heilongjiang provinces, as well as to Russia, the Republic of
Korea and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Farmers pay more attention to nutrition and the quality of food
now and more rural families can afford better electrical
appliances.
</P>
<P>
The rapid growth of the rural economy in the province can be
attributed partly to the efforts made by the local governments at
different levels. Over the past five years, they have spent more
than eight billion yuan (nearly one billion US dollars) on
agricultural development and got 1.6 billion yuan in loans from
the local financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
During the period, 120,000 hectares of mid-yield and low-yield
fields have been improved, and a better flood control and
drought-protection system has been built. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971006.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rusedski Wins ATP Swiss Indoors Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Greg Rusedski, a new rising power
with all-round skills, thrashed Mark Philippoussis in straight
sets to win the million-dollar Swiss Indoors ATP Tour title in
Basel, Switzerland, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 6-3, 7-6 (8/6), 7-6 (7/3) win could push the Briton to
No. 4 in the ATP Tour rankings when they are published on Monday
-- and put him in line for the ATP World Championships in Hanover.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Rusedski, who started the match ranked 10th in
the world had a tough time to win the final.
</P>
<P>
"I think I played very well in the first set and he missed a
couple of volleys that let me in," the Canadian-born Briton said
after his second straight win over the Australian this year
following his Wimbledon triumph.
</P>
<P>
"I want to stay in the top five and try to get to the world
championships in Hanover," he added.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis had prevented the first all-British final since
the Open era dawned in 1968 by beating Britain's Tim Henman in
Saturday's semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
The Australian lost to Germany's Nicolas Kiefer of Germany in
the Toulouse tournament final in France last week.
</P>
<P>
The win was worth 138,000 dollars to Rusedksi, who reached the
quarter-finals at Wimbledon this year before losing to Frenchman
Cedric Pioline and then became the first Briton to make the top
10 by reaching the US Open final at Flushing Meadow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
