<HEADLINE> Protecting Tibetan Cultural Relics and Archives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- An team dispatched by China's
highest legislative body completed a recent fact-finding mission
and confirmed the extensive protection of cultural relics and
historical archives in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The region has effectively protected cultural relics by
enacting a number of local laws and regulations, including the
Administrative Regulations on the Preservation of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the regional government is considering protection
measures for the Potala Palace, the most famous Tibetan lamasery.
</P>
<P>
The regional government, Cultural Relics Bureau and Archives
Bureau of the Region briefed the Law Enforcement Inspection Team
under the National People's Congress (NPC) on the region's efforts
to implement the protection of cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The team, led by Nie Dajiang, vice-chairman of NPC Education,
Science, Culture and Public Health Committee, also conducted
investigations in local areas such as Xigaze Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Team members noted that Tibet's cultural relics and historical
archives have great value in terms of preservation and
research. They also noted that the local government has extended
great efforts to finance relics protection programs.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the importance of protecting cultural relics in
minority areas in order to maintain the country's diverse and rich
cultural traditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
