<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from the Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and France are to launch cooperation in
manufacturing a new automobile called "Kish" with an annual
production of 5,000 units, Iran's official news agency IRNA
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The French Auto Company Renualt will provide 40 percent of the
spare parts, including engines and gears for the new car while
the rest will be produced inside Iran.
</P>
<P>
The car will be ready for marketing in Iran and other parts of
the world by next Spring, said Iranian Industry and Mining Bank
Director General Mojtaba Harati-Nik.
</P>
<P>
As requested by the French side, he added, most of the
products will be re-exported. The car has been successfully
tested by the English company Mayar and will be marketed under an
English license.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A visiting Kuwaiti business delegation Saturday
reached agreements with Jordanian business departments to set up
Kuwaiti investment projects worth more than 200 million
U.S. dollars in Jordan, semi-official Jordan Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The visiting group intended to establish projects in tourism
and health sectors in Aqaba and the Dead Sea areas as well as in
banking sector, the paper quoted Ghazi Saqa'bi, head of the group
and board chairman of financial and real estate companies in
Kuwait, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have started to specify the plots of land where the
projects will be set up," said Saqa'bi.
</P>
<P>
He also said that a Kuwaiti technical team would visit Jordan
next month to complete all the necessary procedures for
establishing the tourism, health and banking investments.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Germany increased its aid to Jordan by 62 million
German marks (about 35 million U.S. dollars) under its 1997 aid
program, German Ambassador to Jordan Peter Mende said.
</P>
<P>
The increase would mainly benefit water and agricultural
projects in the southern Jordan Valley, semi-official Jordan Times
Sunday quoted Mende as saying at a banquet at German embassy in
Amman Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Germany also canceled 40 million marks (about 23 million
dollars) of Jordan's debts owed to Germany, said the German
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The German government endorsed this year's financial assistance
for Jordan, despite the constraints on the fiscal budget, which
reduced the total amount of German assistance to other countries
by 10 percent, Mende said.
</P>
<P>
The original aid from Germany for Jordan this year is 102
million marks (about 58 million dollars), according to Jordan
Times.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Algeria Saturday exchanged documents paving
the way for the establishment of a direct maritime route between
Aqaba and Algerian ports, Sunday's semi-official Jordan Times
reported.
</P>
<P>
This marks the implementation of a protocol concluded during a
visit to Jordan in mid-September by Algerian President Liamine
Zeroual, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Dalabih, director general of the Jordan Ports
Corporation, told a press conference at an inauguration ceremony
aboard the Algerian vessel ``Qasr Al Shallaleh`` that the direct
route would stimulate trade and open the door for further
import-export exchanges by private sectors in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Al Arabi Kharouni, charge d`affaires at the Algerian Embassy
in Jordan, said that the opening of the line aimed to further
strengthen Jordanian-Algerian economic and trade links and to
serve the national interests of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian companies involved in the maritime transport were
showing increased interest in the direct route, because it would
remove barriers obstructing bilateral trade, said Kharouni.
</P>
</TEXT>
