<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drug Created to Treat Multiple-Sclerosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A new drug to treat the
neurological disease Multiple-Sclerosis has been developed in
Israel to effectively reduce the disease's severity, a report said
today.
</P>
<P>
The drug, named Rebif and created by Professor Michel Ravel of
the Weizman Institute, is the second of its kind developed here
for treating Multiple-Sclerosis, a neurological disease that
strikes over a million people around the world, the English daily
the Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
Although Rebif can not cure the disease completely, it could
reduce its severity and frequency of relapsing remitting attacks
by 30 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Clinical trial results on Rebif have been presented on Tuesday
at the 122nd Annual Meeting of the American Neurological
Association in San Diego, California.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted in 22 medical centers in nine other
cities other than Jerusalem. It was the largest study of its kind
ever to investigate a treatment for relapsing-remmiting
Multiple-Sclerosis, a form of the neurological disease that recurs
and causes an accumulation of problems.
</P>
<P>
The new drug is the fourth in the arsenal of neurologists for
treating Multiple-Sclerosis.
</P>
<P>
Rebif will be available in liquid pre-filed syringes for
injections under the skin three times a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
